<HEADLINE> Egyptian President's Attacker to Be Tried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Mustafa Hamza, suspected of
masterminding a 1995 assassination bid against Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa, will be tried in absentia for
planning a series of deadly attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian State Supreme Security Court today decided to
adjourn until September 1 the trial of Hamza along with 21 other
members of the military wing of the Gamaa Islamiya, the main armed
fundamentalist group in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The court, whose verdicts cannot be appealed, made the decision
after listening to the testimony of two state security
investigation officers as witnesses for the prosecution today, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The 22 have been accused of planning attacks on senior
government officials, police and tourists between June 1994 and
March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Other charges include the foundation of an illegal group aimed
at ruining the constitution, precluding public authorities from
exercising their duties and assaulting freedoms and civil rights.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Hamza, two other defendants, Atef Abdel Aziz and
Mohammed Mustafa Hassan, are still at large.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill of indictment, Hamza sent orders and
funds to the group from Sudan, where he has taken refuge. But
Khartoum says Hamza is no longer in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Before they could carry out the attacks, 19 of the militants
were arrested from March 1995 onward in the Cairo and Delta areas
and in the southern Egyptian province of Minya.
</P>
<P>
Hamza, who is considered Gamaa Islamiya's military chief
abroad, was sentenced to death in absentia in 1993 for involvement
in the assassination attempt against Information Minister Safwat
Al Sherif.
</P>
<P>
He is one of three Egyptians whose extradition from Sudan has
been demanded by the U.N. Security Council so they can be tried in
Addis Ababa for the June 1995 assassination attempt on Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
In the incident, five or six gunmen shot at Mubarak's motorcade
shortly after arriving in Addis Ababa on June 26, before he
returned home safe on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
