<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Government Probes HK Governor Patten: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- An investigation has begun in the
British government into allegations that former Governor of Hong
Kong Chris Patten leaked classified intelligence documents, a
government minister said today.
</P>
<P>
"All I know is that the issue...rather the individual is under
investigation by the authorities," Minister Without Portfolio
Peter Mandelson told BBC Radio.
</P>
<P>
"That will be done in a proper, objective and authoritative
way," Mandelson said.
</P>
<P>
Confirmation of the official probe came after The Sunday Times
said Foreign Office officials are pressing for Patten to be
prosecuted under Britain's Official Secrets Act. It said MI6,
Britain's overseas security service, is investigating the case.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson said authorities "have no alternative but to
investigate it when allegations are made that secret intelligence
material has been passed to individuals outside."
</P>
<P>
"It would be irresponsible for the government not to take the
action when there appears to have been a leak of intelligence
material of this kind," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
