<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Conditionally Allow GSP for Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC) has
expressed its readiness to accept some derogation from rules of
origin in importing Bangladeshi garment products on some
conditions, an official handout said here today.
</P>
<P>
The EC's acceptance, on condition of withdrawal of erroneous
GSP (generalized system of preference) certificates from 1993-96,
came today in response to a letter from Bangladeshi Commerce and
Industries Minister Tofail Ahmed, said the handout.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been enjoying the GSP facilities in the EU
countries since 1986 with duty-free entry without any quota
restrictions. But the products must be made of indigenous
materials to get the facilities.
</P>
<P>
In case of knitwear, as per rules of the GSP, entrepreneurs may
import raw materials like wool and cotton but they must go through
three stages like preparing yarn and fabrics for knitwear
products.
</P>
<P>
The EU, however, imposed some restrictions on exporting
knitwear from Bangladesh late last year on a plea that about 8,000
forged GSP certificates were issued to some knitwear exporters who
have not gone through three-stage local transformation.
</P>
<P>
A delegation from Bangladesh led by Tofail Ahmed visited
Brussels in January this year and called on the EC to consider
relaxation of the country of origin rule.
</P>
<P>
On July 29, Tofail in his letter again urged the EU to find
some ways, if necessary at political level, to resolve the
problems with a flexible attitude.
</P>
<P>
EC official Mario Monti in his letter to Tofail said the EU is
ready to accept a two-stage local transformation instead of the
three-stage one provided the GSP system is applied correctly in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, according to official sources, has yet to decide on
this critical issue because of the apprehension that once the
forged GSP certificates were officially admitted, this will not
only create image problem for Bangladeshi exporters but also may
make them liable to pay compensation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
