<HEADLINE> Flood Danger Eases in Eastern Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The threat of massive flooding in
eastern Germany has eased for the first time since nearly three
weeks ago as water levels began to recede slowly overnight along
the whole stretch of the swollen Oder River on the German-Polish
border.
</P>
<P>
But local officials stressed that the situation remained
dangerous because water mass continued to put high pressure on the
waterlogged dikes.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers and soldiers were still working hard to repair
leaks in water defenses throughout the most vulnerable Oderbruch
region in the north as the latest reports said that two new cracks
were discovered in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
It would take at least another week for floodwaters to fall to
a safe level, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The flood over the past weeks has ravaged thousands of homes
and claimed the lives of 105 people in Poland and the Czech
Repubic. Germany has so far escaped the worst of the disaster with
only several villages flooded but no casualties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
