<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-03 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Tries Hard to Prevent Violent Attack: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
said today that the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) is doing
everything in its power to prevent Islamic extremists from
launching violent attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub, head of the Palestinian Preventive Security
Service in the West Bank, told reporters that the PNA has done
more than Israel is aware of, according to a report of the
state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
However, he declared that the PNA will not accept dictates
from the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub said that in order to wipe out terrorism, Israel must
back up and support PNA President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the Israeli and Palestinian security
officials are working together to investigate the double suicide
bombing in Jerusalem Wednesday. A total of 13 Israelis were
killed and some 170 injured in the terror attack.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub said that the current situation is not suitable for a
full resumption of security cooperation between the two sides,
which broke off after Israel began construction of the Har Homa
Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
Rajoub's counterpart in the Gaza Strip, Mohammed Dahlan, said
in Gaza Saturday that the Palestinians would not take orders from
Israel.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Palestinian side has cut off
security coordination with Israel. He added that such
cooperation would not resume until Israel implements agreements
it signed with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
