<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bank of England Governor Might Be Reappointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Eddie George's term as governor of
the Bank of England still has a year to run, but candidates are
already queuing up to become his successor.
</P>
<P>
Mervyn King, the bank's director of economics, has made no
secret of his desire to become governor. Gavyn Davies, head of
economics at Goldman Sachs and a close adviser to Chancellor
Gordon Brown, has also been linked with the post.
</P>
<P>
However, reports here today said that Prime Minister Tony Blair
has intervened to end speculation that Eddie George will be
replaced as Bank of England governor.
</P>
<P>
Treasury insiders say the prime minister has accepted City and
business advice that George's continued role as governor is an
essential prerequisite for financial stability and economic policy
credibility.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed in the City that Blair's intervention
put an end to a campaign to insert Gavyn Davies as governor, but
the campaign to secure a governor who is perceived to be more
Treasury-friendly has not fizzled out altogether.
</P>
<P>
There is mounting speculation that George will be reappointed
for two years rather than the full term. The prospect of
appointment to governor in the year 2000 is thought to be
sufficiently tantalizing to retain the interest of potential
candidates.
</P>
<P>
However, City specialists said a two-year appointment would be
illegal under current legislation. The law dictates that the
governor must be appointed by the queen on the prime minister's
recommendation for a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
A two-year appointment could only be secured by a side deal
involving a promise from the governor that he would retire less
than half way through his second term.
</P>
<P>
Before the general election, George, who will be 60 next year,
hinted that he may not want to serve a second full term. Recently,
however, he has made it clear he is determined to serve a full
five years.
</P>
<P>
Confirmation that George is to be reappointed as governor will
bring relief to the City and financial markets, which had become
uneasy at the speculation apparently designed to undermine his
position.
</P>
<P>
George has received public and private backing from the
international banking community. It is this pressure that has
forced Blair to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe the decision by Blair to take such an
active interest in the appointment is being interpreted in some
quarter as a sign of growing tension between the prime minister
and the chancellor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Prices in UK at 8-Year Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Housing prices in Britain are at
their highest level since 1989 and have risen by 1.8 percent since
June, according to Nationwide's house-price index.
</P>
<P>
Housing prices are now 12.2 percent higher than they were this
time last year. The increase is greatest in London and has been
caused predominantly by a shortage of properties in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Sales throughout the country, however, are "historically" low
at the moment, said Nationwide, but are expected to improve over
the next few months as higher prices encourage more properties on
to the market.
</P>
<P>
Paul Sanderson, Nationwide's head of research, said there were
already signs of this happening in London, reinforced by a sharp
decline in negative-equity cases.
</P>
<P>
"First-time buyers who were able to buy better houses and
leapfrog the cheaper properties in the 1980s are now being pushed
further downmarket," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sanderson said that the market was not as strong as the price
rises suggested and said the increase in house prices was expected
to drop to 9 percent by the end of the year. 
</P>
