<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weis Wins Men's Hammer Gold in World Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Heinz Weis of Germany tossed 81.78
meters to win the men's hammer gold medal at the 6th World Athletics
Championships here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The German, who set the year's best mark of 83.04 before the meet,
beat Andrey Skvaruk of Ukraine on the final round with his mighty
winner. Skvaruk, who led the first five outings, finished second at
81.46, his best mark this year.
</P>
<P>
Vasiliy Sidorenko of Russia, the 1994 European champion, took the
bronze with a 80.76 heave, well out of his season's best 82.90.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Balazs Kiss of Hungary wound up fourth at 79.96.
World silver medallist Igor Astapkovich of Belarus was beaten into
fifth place at 79.70.
</P>
<P>
Weis beamed after the victory, saying:"With my new coach I have
learned to take high risks and still retain a perfect throw. That is
the secret of my victory. This helped me get over my first weak throw,
which we all had because of the long pause between warming up and
competition."
</P>
<P>
Skvaruk said that the start of the final showed that all the
competitors were very nervous. "Now I have nearly lost my voice by
supporting the flight of my hammer. Each time after my throw, I
shouted 'go, go, fly, fly!' I will celebrate after going home."
</P>
</TEXT>
