<HEADLINE> Russia Seeking Links With Ukrainian Navy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Council Secretary
Yuri Baturin said today that the main tasks of the Russian Black
Sea Fleet during military reform are to increase its combat
readiness and step up interaction with the Ukrainian navy.
</P>
<P>
The key problem is not reform itself but the implementation of
the agreements signed by the Russian and Ukrainian prime
ministers in Kiev on May 28, the Interfax news agency quoted
Baturin as saying.
</P>
<P>
"After everything (as regards the Black Sea Fleet) is divided,
it is necessary to learn how to interact," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Baturin noted Russia and Ukraine have so far not settled
problems pertaining to the air navigation servicing of Black Sea
Fleet ships and air power, navigation support in the Black Sea and
the Sea of Azov, the distribution of radio frequencies and the
recognition of the Black Sea Fleet's ownership rights to housing
in Sevastopol.
</P>
<P>
Baturin said that he disagreed to the statements that after its
division, the Black Sea Fleet had ceased to be a military unit to
be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
"During the fleet's division, 388 of the 525 ships and vessels
were passed on to Russia. Fifty of the 68 military ships became
Russian," he said.
</P>
<P>
The fleet is not only ships but also infrastructure, Baturin
said, adding that "the Russian fleet's corresponding interests in
Sevastopol have been ensured." 
</P>
</TEXT>
