<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Spreading in Belarus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The head of the Republican Center
for the prevention of AIDS, Valery Glozovsky, said today that the
HIV infection is spreading rapidly in Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported from Minsk, capital of
Belarus, that last year alone, the number of HIV-positive cases
diagnosed rose tenfold against the overall figures for the period
from 1987 through 1995.
</P>
<P>
In total, 492 HIV-positive cases were reported during
January-June 1997.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,627 people suffering from AIDS have been
registered to date in the country, including 1,102 people in the
town of Svetlogorsk, Gomel region.
</P>
<P>
According to Glozovsky, Svetlogorsk is a town of drug addicts
and the AIDS epidemic is spreading chiefly out of this town.
</P>
<P>
"HIV-infected persons mostly include young people using drugs
intravenously," the head said. Such developments may spawn
unpredictable consequences leading to "infected young people dying
of AIDS in five to seven years," Glozovsky warned.
</P>
<P>
AIDS is spreading in particular because narcotic drugs are
cheap in the country: they cost up to 100,000 Belarussian rubles
(about 3.3 U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
By now there have been no cases of children becoming infected
in Belarussian medical care establishments, Glozovsky said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Declaration of War Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu rejected today the Palestinian claim that the
security measures taken by Israeli cabinet were "declaration of
war" against all Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the weekly cabinet session that the peace
process could not advance if the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) did not launch war on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the future of the peace process depends on PNA
President Yasser Arafat, adding that Israel could not keep its
commitments unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
In his telephone conversation Saturday with U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross, who is to arrive here at the end of the week on a
mission to revive the Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation,
Netanyahu declared that everything hinges on the PNA's actions
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks after hearing the briefings by
Israeli security officials on the cabinet on the situation in the
Palestinian territories, who said Arafat still had not ordered a
large-scaled crackdown on terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai claimed that the PNA was
only conducting small and localized operations against the
anti-Israeli organizations, such as the Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) and Islamic Jihad, instead of a wide-scaled
campaign to smash the terrorist and its support infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel was keeping the pressure on Arafat to step
up crackdown on terrorist organizations. He added that Israel
has frozen transfer of funds to the PNA and any future
unfreezing was dependent on PNA's war against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan said the government should
inform the United States and European countries that if terrorist
activities came from the Palestinian-controlled areas, Israel
would exercise its right of self-defense by sending security
forces into the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Eitan added that it was desirable that both U.S. and
Europe exert pressure on Arafat to take actions so that
Israel would not have to implement the option of sending
troops back to Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub, head of the Palestinian Preventive Security
Service in West Bank, refuted Israeli accusations today, saying
that the PNA is doing its utmost to prevent terrorist attacks and
will not accept dictates from the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
PNA security chief in Gaza Strip Mohammed Dahlan also said
that Palestinians would not take orders from Israel. He said
Palestinian security forces have cut off security cooperation
with Israel, which would not resume until Israel implements
the peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that current security meetings between the two
sides were conducted only within the framework of the
investigation into the Wednesday twin suicide bombings in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, which killed 15 people and
wounded 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for the terror attack,
although Israel is questioning the authenticity of the claim.
Israeli and Palestinian security forces have since carried out
a widespread crackdown on Hamas and Islamic Jihad by rounding
up a number of their activists.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces were put on high alert today amid
intelligence warnings about possible new terror attacks. Police
reinforcements were deployed in major cities such Jerusalem and
Tel Aviv, setting up road blocks at city entrances to
increase security checks. Police have received hundreds of calls
from the public to report on suspicious bags and cars, which
were suspected to be bobby-trapped by terrorists.
</P>
</TEXT>
