<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Ensures Jordanian Route for Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has assured Amman of the
continuous using of Jordan's Red Sea port of Aqaba as a key route
for receiving humanitarian goods despite of the planned opening of
a supply line through Syria.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Iraqi Minister of Commerce Mohammed Mehdi Saleh made
the promise at a meeting with his Jordanian counterpart Hani
Moulki here today.
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan quoted Moulki as saying that Iraq will double its
imports via Aqaba -- more than that witnessed in the first phase
of the oil-for-food deal reached between Iraq and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The deal allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil over a six-month period to buy back food and medicines badly
needed in the U.N. sanctions-stricken country. The first phase
started last December and has been renewed for another six months.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's promise came as Baghdad applied to the U.N. for the
opening of the Iraq-Syria border. This route, if approved by the
U.N., will facilitate the flow-in of the Syrian-made goods cheaper
than Jordanian products and provide European exporters a route
shorter than the Aqaba one.
</P>
<P>
The action has triggered fear among the Jordanian businessmen
of losing business with Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Saleh also promised to increase imports from Jordan, but
stopping short of elaborating on specific volume, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been Jordan's largest trade partner for years, with
its exports of goods and services to Iraq totalled 220 million
U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also asked to transform the 11 million dollars worth of
service items in its 255 million dollars trade protocol with
Jordan, which was signed at the beginning of this year and exempt
from the oil-for-food deal, into commodity items, Moulki added.
</P>
<P>
Via Aqaba port, Iraq imported civilian goods and military
equipment during the Iraqi-Iranian war in the 1980s and Jordan
made more than 1 billion dollars every year from entrepot trade
through Aqaba port bound for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, the Aqaba port lost its glory when the U.N. sanctions
was imposed on Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. Iraq has
relied more on its border with Turkey as well as its own Um Qasr
port, both of which were approved by the U.N. under the
oil-for-food deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Produces Less Fertilizer in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS,August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's fertilizer production
fell to 607,339.6 tons in 1996 from 1995's 1,072,561.3 tons, down
by 43 percent, the News Agency of Nigeria said today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a report of the Central Bank of Nigeria as
saying that the capacity utilization of Nigerian fertilizer
plants averaged merely 45 percent, compared to nearly 88 percent
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Super-sulphate Fertilizer Company in Kaduna State
which produces super-sulphate and alum recorded a drop by 35
percent in its production from 4,251 tons of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The National Fertilizer Company in Onne also saw a 43 percent
decline in its production of urea and ammonia, with a total
output of 604,583 tons.
</P>
<P>
The fall in production has caused a shortage of fertilizers,
the bank report said, adding that inadequate funding and the lack
of raw materials and plant spare parts are responsible for the
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
