<HEADLINE> Greene Claims Men's 100m Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Maurice Greene of the United States
bolted off the blocks fast and maintained the lead to win the men's
100 meters gold medal with a season's best time of 9.86 seconds at the
6th World Athletics Championships here Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
His winning time is the fourth best all time, and only 0.02 seconds
outside the world record.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion and world record holder Donovan Bailey of Canada
was second in 9.91 ahead of another American Tim Montgomery's 9.94.
</P>
<P>
The pre-race favourite Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tobago lost his
edge in the final somehow, finishing fifth in 10.02. His leg seemed
injuried at the end of the race.
</P>
<P>
Olympic silver medallist Frank Fredericks of Namibia was fourth in
9.95.
</P>
<P>
The showdown to decide the fastest man in the world was expected to
produce a new world record, and many thought that Boldon would beat
the 9.84 mark with ease. The Olympic bronze medal winner ran 9.87 in
the second round yesterday and looked in a super form.
</P>
<P>
Greene, who clocked 9.90 at the U.S.A. Championships last June,
showed his strength in the semifinal with a 9.90 clocking. It is his
first medal in world major competitions. 
</P>
