<HEADLINE> US to Help African Countries Clear Land-mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States is reviewing
its policy on Africa in order to assist more countries in
clearing millions of deadly land mines which kill and maim
thousands of lives annually.
</P>
<P>
After touring mine fields in the Victoria Falls area, visiting
U.S. forces deputy commander in chief for Europe and Africa,
James Jamerson today said his government, already assisting
Namibia, Mozambique and Rwanda, is considering widening the area.
</P>
<P>
"The decision of expanding our assistance to other African
countries will be made very soon and Zimbabwe's candidature is
very favorable," he said, adding, "the U.S. and Zimbabwe are
already cooperating militarily in the fields of training,
peace-keeping and humanitarian relief."
</P>
<P>
"As you are aware, Zimbabwe is part of the U.S. initiative of
the African crisis response focused on provision of basic
soldiery equipment, training, peace-keeping and relief efforts,
Jamerson said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "the U.S. is currently talking with its western
allies to enhance the African military capacity for these
duties.''
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. government has no plan to deploy its forces
in Africa as in other continents.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe National Army (ZNA) needs at least 13.6 million
U.S. Dollars to rid the country of the estimated two million
mines scattered along the border areas.
</P>
<P>
General Jamerson is on a three-day visit to the country, which
he described as maintaining military contact between the two
countries. He will hold meeting Monday with Zimbabwean Defense
Minister Moven Mahachi and high ranking defense force officers.
</P>
<P>
He has already been to Senegal, Cote d'Ivore and Gabon and
will leave Tuesday for Namibia, Mozambique and Uganda to conclude
the 10-day African trip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
