<HEADLINE> US Urges Palestinians to Fight Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- As Israel beefs up security to
guard off more terrorist attacks, senior U.S. officials put more
pressure today on the Palestinian leadership to fight extremists.
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said on CBS "Face the
Nation" that Palestinians must step up security controls to prove
they are serious about fighting terrorism, a condition under which
the Middle East peace talks could proceed.
</P>
<P>
"One can't expect 100 percent results when you're fighting
terrorism. But there can be a total, 100 percent unrelenting
effort," he believed.
</P>
<P>
"I think the effort's been uneven. It has to intensify" to ease
Israelis' anxiety, he added.
</P>
<P>
Berger also urged Israel, for its part, to assure the
Palestinians that it is not trying to pre-empt later negotiations
by building more Jewish housing units in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement following a double suicide market bombing
in Jerusalem last week, which killed 15 people and wounded more
than 150 others.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat immediately condemned the bomb
attack, vowing to fight the terrorists with all his strength. The
Palestinian National Authority (PNC) has arrested a large number
of Hamas activists, according to early reports.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has been opposed to the peace talks with Israel. Its
military wing has claimed responsibility for the latest suicide
bombing.
</P>
<P>
"We have to have a higher degree of security cooperation. This
is not only in the interest of Israel; in my judgment, it's in the
interest of the Palestinian people," Berger stressed.
</P>
<P>
Arafat went to Cairo Saturday to seek Egyptian backing amid
reports that Israeli troops might storm back to the PNC-controlled
areas to punish the Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader called the Israeli threat a "declaration
of war" against the Palestinians. The exchange of harsh
accusations has made the situation in the troubled region more
tense.
</P>
<P>
In Israel today, the security forces set up roadblocks and
checkpoints on roads leading to Jerusalem in precaution against
possible new terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich called today for
harsher steps to combat terrorism, including raids to the
Palestinian territory and arrests of PNC leaders.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on "Fox News Sunday," Gingrich said that Arafat had
lost credibility in Congress, which would decide after a
month-long recess if the Palestinians would deserve continued U.S.
aid after a law in this respect expires on August 12.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erakat told CNN today that
the PNC had dealt a severe blow to terrorists or would-be
terrorists. But he added that it remained unclear who exactly
perpetrated the last week attack.
</P>
<P>
Washington postponed a trip to the Middle East by special
coordinator Denny Ross following the bomb attack, despite the Arab
and Palestinian cry for prompt U.S. actions to salvage the
Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
