<HEADLINE> Tanzania Blocks Congolese Refugees From Secret </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has blocked about
500 Congolese (K) refugees from sneaking out of the camps at
Kigoma in western Tanzania to former Zaire until formalities of
their return are finalized by the relevant authorities.
</P>
<P>
Kigoma regional Commissioner Yusuf Makamba told the official
Daily News over the telephone from Kigoma today that 400 were
blocked last Friday and about 50 more last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Makamba said, "the 400 Congolese refugees and the other group
of 50 were blocked from boarding boats plying in Lake Tanganyika
suspected to be taking them home."
</P>
<P>
The regional commissioner said all the refugees who were
intercepted were returned to their respective camps.
</P>
<P>
He explained that refugees started sneaking out of the camps
after knowing that President William Mkapa who visited Democratic
Congo last week had agreed with his host -- President Laurent
Kabila that the Congolese refugees should return home.
</P>
<P>
Makamba said he was part of the President's entourage and that
it was decided during the talks of the two leaders that the
refugees would return home through a process.
</P>
<P>
He said that it now upon the United Nations High Commission
for Refugees (UNHCR) and the ministry of home affairs to finalize
formalities and issues "movement order" for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
"The refugees must leave Tanzania (Kigoma) formally and
officials in Congo have to receive them formally. They have
stayed here as refugees for quite a while ad there are norms
governing such movement which the government of Tanzania and
Congo must observe," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the regional commissioner said, "It is important
that the UNHCR repairs the roads ad other things for good
preparation of returning the Congolese. UNHCR trucks will make
several trips to the camps to pick them (refugees) and roads are
currently is in a very bad state."
</P>
<P>
"If the refugees will be allowed to leave tomorrow the UNHCR
will never come back to repair these public roads as a result the
peasants will suffer for no apparent reason simply because the
issue is being mishandled by the UNHCR," he said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 100,000 Congolese refugees in Kigoma region
who fled their country late last year following the civil strife
that culminated in the removal of Mobutu Sese Seko"s regime last
May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
