<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Price Recovers Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The average price of a basket of
OPEC seven crude oils rose to 18.29 dollars per barrel last week
from 17.82 dollars a week earlier, the oil cartel's secretariat
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The price has edged up gradually since the end of June after
oil ministers from OPEC (Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries) agreed to freeze their production quotas for six
months in a bid to boost prices.
</P>
<P>
The monthly average price in June was 17.37 dollars per
barrel. The average price so far this year is 19.01 dollars, lower
than OPEC's benchmark 21 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The July rise reverses a declining trend evident since the
start of the year.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have fallen steadily from a peak of 25 dollars a
barrel in January partly because of the prospect of Iraq entering
the oil market again after a temporary lifting of sanctions by the
United Nations and partly because over overproduction by OPEC
members, most of whom have been breaking their quotas designed to
keep prices up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
