<HEADLINE> EU Bans Fish Imports From Bangladesh, India, Madagascar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has banned
all imports of fishery products from Bangladesh, India and
Madagascar for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
The ban, effective last Friday, will last at least till
November 30 when EU ministers meet to discuss the matter again.
</P>
<P>
The ban was made after officials from the European Commission's
food and veterinary office inspected the fish processing plants in
the three countries and found "serious deficiencies in the
structure of establishments, hygiene quality of raw material and
in processing operations."
</P>
<P>
Fishery products already bound for EU countries, however, may
be admitted before August 15 after satisfactory sample tests.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, India and Madagascar exported a total of 320
million Ecus (342 million U.S. dollars) worth of fishery products
to EU countries in 1996. 
</P>
