<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Launch New Ruble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
announced today that Russia will issue new ruble notes next year
with face values 1,000 times greater than the current notes.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank will issue new notes and coins on January 1 to
replace the old ones and one new ruble will equal 1,000 current
rubles, Yeltsin said in a Kremlin statement.
</P>
<P>
"The three excessive zeroes will disappear from the
notes, ... one will pay one ruble for the product that had a 1,000
ruble price-tag on it," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Old notes will remain in use next year, and then be phased out
of circulation by January 1, 1999. To avoid any panic on currency
exchanges, Yeltsin said, old notes can be exchanged in banks until
2002.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said the reform is a result of improved currency
stability after years of inflation curbing measures. "Today we
reliably control money circulation and control inflation. People
know that we no longer have a rapid growth of prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In doing so we declare that there will be no more
inflation," he said. "An end has been put to it."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said Russia has recovered from the crisis of
hyperinflation which engulfed the country in the early
1990s. Inflation soared to 2,500 percent in 1992, a year after the
collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Ruble notes currently range from the relatively worthless 100
rubles (0.17 U.S. cents) to 100,000 rubles, which sounds
impressive but is only worth 17 dollars. The new notes will have
dominations of five rubles (86 U.S. cents), 10 rubles (1.7
dollars), 50 rubles (8.6 dollars), 100 rubles (17 dollars) and 500
rubles (86 dollars), Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank will also issue one, two and five-ruble coins
and restart using Kopeck coins. One hundred Kopecks will equal one
ruble.
</P>
<P>
Federal and regional budgets and other calculations for 1998
will be in new rubles, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Economic Minister Yakov Urinson said that
redenomination will not affect prices, but financial experts said
a sudden rise in prices is possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
