<HEADLINE> SAARC to Hold Fair and Meeting for Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The second trade fair of the
South Asian Association For Regional Cooperation (SAARC) will be
held in Pakistan on February 16-20, 1998, while commerce ministers
from the member states will meet to discuss free trade in the
region, the SAARC secretary-general said here today.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with a 25-member delegation of the SAARC
Chamber of Commerce and Industry (SCCI) at the Kathmandu-based
SAARC Secretariat, SAARC Secretary-General Naeem U. Hasan stressed
the increasing role of the private sector, in particular the SCCI,
in accelerating trade and economic cooperation and achieving a
South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA).
SAARC members agreed at a May summit to set up the SAFTA by 2001.
</P>
<P>
SAARC members began their third round of trade negotiations in
late July to move from the South Asian Preferential Trading
Arrangement to SAFTA.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the SAARC secretariat quoted Salman
F. Rahman, president of the SCCI based in Karachi, Pakistan, as
saying that the SCCI will continue to take active interest in the
SAARC activities, particularly in the field of trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the SCCI will be actively participating in the second
SAARC trade fair and will concurrently hold the second SAARC
Economic Cooperation Conference in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the SCCI is planning activities for promotion
of tourism in the region.
</P>
<P>
The first SAARC trade fair and the first SAARC commerce
ministers meeting were held in January, 1996 in New Delhi, India.
</P>
<P>
SAARC now groups India, Nepal, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan,
Sri Lanka and the Maldives.  
</P>
