<HEADLINE> Cambodian Parliament to Vote on New First PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen said today that parliament will vote on Wednesday to
decide who will succeed ousted first prime minister Prince Norodom
Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
In a statement signed today, Hun Sen called for exiled
opposition legislators, officials and military officers to return
home by Wednesday to take part in the vote.
</P>
<P>
"The royal government wishes to appeal to you (legislators)
once again to join the meeting of the National Assembly which is
expecting to vote on your confidence in the candidate for
nomination of first prime minister of the Kingdom of Cambodia on
Wednesday," the statement, read on national television, said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen promised that supporters of the ousted prince would
remain in their former positions and that they and their families
would be guaranteed safety and security.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia was now calm and the parliament was functioning
normally, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the call two days after meeting a delegation of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in Phnom Penh
and called for the return of exiled opposition figures.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN team asked Hun Sen to make an announcement at "the
highest possible level" that FUNCIPEC officials and MPs would be
able to return home safely and without fear of "persecution or
intimidation" to take part in the political process, including
the choice of a new premier.
</P>
<P>
The royalist FUNCINPEC party named Foreign Minister Ung Huot to
succeed Ranariddh, who was deposed by his rival Hun Sen after
heavy fighting in the capital in early July between troops loyal
to the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Some 18 opposition FUNCINPEC members have fled the country
since the fighting, amid allegations of arrests, torture and
extra-judicial murders of the party's officials who did not get
away. 
</P>
