<HEADLINE> Shevardnadze Warns Russia over Abkhazia Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze today warned Russia that any lifting of economic
sanctions against Abkhazia would strain Georgia-Russia relations.
</P>
<P>
"If Russia in a unilateral way annuls the economic sanctions
adopted against Abkhazia, this could lead to serious complications
in Georgian-Russian relations," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted
the Georgian president as telling national radio in Tblisi.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia, a breakaway enclave in Georgia, declared independence
in July, 1992.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said that the economic sanctions against Abkhazia
were introduced in light of the decision of the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) Council of Heads of State.
</P>
<P>
He said the unilateral lifting of the sanctions would be
unacceptable and would damage the authority of the CIS.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze called "illogical" the statements by some Russian
politicians that economic sanctions on Abkhazia are no longer in
Russia's interests and that it is time to discuss lifting them.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that only a summit of CIS leaders could decide the
sanctions issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
