<HEADLINE> UN Envoy to Meet Afghan Faction Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Continuing his mission of
persuasion for peace in Afghanistan, UN Special Envoy Nobert Holl
will meet leaders of the northern alliance on Tuesday in
Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 km northwest of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Holl, who leaves here for the stronghold of the alliance
opposing the Islamic Taliban militia on Tuesday morning, will take
up the issue of releasing some senior Taliban officials detained
in Mazar-e-Sharif, a UN official said today.
</P>
<P>
The formation of a political commission will also figure in the
talks between Holl and the alliance leaders, he said.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance led mainly by Afghanistan's former
military chief Ahmad Masood and Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik has
forwarded the idea of setting up a political commission for the
formation of a broad-based government in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban have advocated that the political
commission should include all Afghan groups, small and large, and
not just the northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad Omar, supreme leader of the Taliban, has also set the
release of their prisoners as a pre-condition for entering into
meaningful peace talks while the anti-Taliban alliance demanded
the demilitarization of Kabul before agreeing to a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UN official also dispelled the impression that
the appointment of Lakhdar Brahimi for assessing the Afghanistan
situation for UN's further action is an expression of
no-confidence in the Holl mission.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, former Algerian foreign minister, has been assigned by
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan to send back an in-depth account
of the Afghanistan situation before the UN General Assembly
session in September.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian diplomat is expected to arrive here next week. He
will assess the UN peace-making efforts and hold talks with Afghan
factions and consult with "relevant countries."  
</P>
</TEXT>
