<HEADLINE> Denktash's Decision to Attend Talks Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
welcomed the decision by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to
attend the second round of U.N.-sponsored direct talks, scheduled
for August 11-16.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome Denktash's decision to go to Switzerland. Each
side will outline its views and arguments at the talks next
week," government spokesman Manolis Christofides said at his daily
press briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side, he added, "will discuss in good faith
every aspect of the Cyprus problem to find solutions to each one
of them."
</P>
<P>
Denktash's decision to take part in the direct talks was
announced earlier today after he consulted with his self-styled
cabinet in northern part of Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared unilaterally a breakaway
state "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which
was only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Denktash threatened not to go to the talks unless
the European Union suspended the accession negotiations with
Cyprus, due to begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Denktash met last month
at Troutbeck, near New York, in the first round of direct talks
sponsored by the U.N. for the first time in nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
They had two meetings last week in Nicosia under the auspices
of the U.N. Resident Representative on the island, Gustave
Feissel, to discuss humanitarian issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
