<HEADLINE> HK Police Intercept Illegal Vietnamese Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Police intercepted 11
illegal Vietnamese immigrants on Lantau, Hong Kong, today, and
will repatriate them as soon as possible, a security department
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
In response to reporters' inquiries, the spokesman also said
that "the police are searching for any other illegal Vietnamese
immigrants who may have escaped."
</P>
<P>
The captured Vietnamese immigrants are still being
investigated, he noted, stressing that all the illegal immigrants
intercepted "will be repatriated to Vietnam as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
"The illegal Vietnamese immigrants come to Hong Kong to seek
illegal employment and make money. Whether there is any first
asylum policy or not would not have any impact on the attraction
of Hong Kong for them," he explained.
</P>
<P>
A source in the Information Department of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region's government told Xinhua tonight that there
are a total of 3,400 illegal Vietnamese immigrants now in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Among them, some 1,800, found to be non-refugees, would have to
return to Vietnam soon either voluntarily or under an Orderly
Repatriation Program (ORP) as agreed with the Vietnamese
government in 1991, the source said, adding that some 1,300
others, found to be refugees, are waiting for resettlement in
related countries.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier statistics from the local information
department, over 200,000 Vietnamese "asylum seekers" have arrived
in Hong Kong since 1975, and from 1988 it was apparent that most
Vietnamese arriving in Hong Kong were "economic migrants," who had
no hope of overseas resettlement.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, when a breakthrough was achieved in securing a
practicable solution to the Vietnamese immigrants, most of the
illegal Vietnamese immigrants have returned home voluntarily or
have been repatriated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
