<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Olympic Champion Windsurfer Awarded with Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's famed woman
windsurfer Lee Lai-shan was on Monday awarded with prize money
from the local sports authority and an Olympic golden pin from the
International Olympic Committee (IOC).
</P>
<P>
The Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee (ASF&AMP;OC) of
Hong Kong awarded the 26-year-old athlete 1,237,000 HK dollars
(158,600 U.S. dollars) for her achievement, including her victory
in the women's Mistral boardsailing event at last year's Atlanta
Olympic Games. It was Hong Kong's first ever Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
And the Windsurfing Association of Hong Kong and the Hong Kong
Yachting Association were each presented with 206,200 HK dollars
(26,400 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
All the prize money was from the proceeds of the Olympic
Postcards put on sale in Hong Kong last October by the local
General Post Office for the ASF&AMP;OC.
</P>
<P>
Lee was also awarded with an Olympic Golden Pin, a special
honor from the IOC for all Olympic gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
With 86 medals already to her credit, Lee has set her next
major target at the 1998 Asian Games in Bangkok. And that is just
what the ASF&AMP;OC wants her to do next year. "The gold medal at the
Bangkok Asian Games is now up to grab and that is the medal we
want her to win," said ASF&AMP;OC President A. de O. Sales at today's
awarding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"You could put it in the same deposit box with your Olympic
gold medal, for which I bet," Sales joked.
</P>
<P>
With that goal achieved, Lee would complete her collection of
top honors -- gold medals from the world championships, Olympic
Games, Asian Games and Asian championships.
</P>
<P>
But an Olympic triumph does not necessarily mean that she could
outshine others again at the Asian Games. At least Lee herself
does not look that way.
</P>
<P>
Having missed out that title two times, the Asian Games
silver-medalist said, "There is no guarantee that this time I will
win."
</P>
<P>
"The Olympics and Asian Games are completely different, in
terms of conditions and opponents," she said after today's
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"I'll do my best to win, but that'll be tough, " she said.
</P>
<P>
Lee and her teammate and boyfriend Sam Wong Tak-sum returned
from the Isewan Cup in Nagoya, central Japan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"My performance there was not satisfactory, but at least I've
learnt in what shape I am now," she said.
</P>
<P>
Lack of preparations was one of the reasons for her less
impressive show at the event, she admitted. She finished second
in the Open category in Nagoya.
</P>
<P>
She had not practiced on sailboard for long since she went to
Canberra in March this year to complete the penultimate collegiate
course of the sports management degrees.
</P>
<P>
Lee and Wong came back to Hong Kong just days before the
handover for ceremonies and celebrations around July 1 this year,
and only from then on she resumed serious training to improve her
form.
</P>
<P>
Lee said she plans to leave here later this month for
Zhanjiang, South China, for the coming Asia-Pacific championships.
</P>
<P>
"It's a good warm-up for the Bangkok Asian Games," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
