<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Suffers Billion Dollar Trade Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a trade
deficit of 2.7 billion ringgit (about 1.08 billion U.S. dollars)
in the first half of this year, mainly due to a huge deficit in
June, according to official statistics released today.
</P>
<P>
Trade deficit in the first half of last year was 687.8 million
ringgit (about 275.12 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In June alone, the country posted a trade deficit of 2.8
billion ringgit (about 1.12 billion dollars) against a surplus of
156.2 million ringgit (about 62.48 million dollars) in May, the
Statistics Department said in its external trade summary for
January-June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report said the deficit in June was caused by the purchase
of ships and tankers and commercial aircraft, collectively worth
2.2 billion ringgit (about 880 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Imports in this year's first half were worth 101.1 billion
ringgit (about 40.44 billion dollars), 4 percent higher than the
97.2 billion ringgit (about 38.88 billion dollars) registered in
the same period last year, the Statistics Department said .
</P>
<P>
Exports in the period rose by 1.9 percent to 98.4 billion
ringgit (about 39.36 billion dollars) from 96.6 billion ringgit
(about 38.64 billion dollars) in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Statistics Department said the deficit was partly
attributed to increased imports in transport equipment and office
data processing equipment which valued at 1.4 billion ringgit
(about 560 million dollars) and 1.1 billion ringgit (about 440
million dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
On export, the department said thermionic valves and tubes,
photocells, and parts continued to be the country's largest export
earners, accounting for 18.4 percent of the total export earnings.
</P>
<P>
For the first half, Malaysia's major trading partners included
Japan, the United States, Singapore, South Korea, Thailand,
Germany, the United Kingdom, China and the Netherlands, which
collectively accounted for 79.9 percent of Malaysia's total trade,
the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
