<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK to Prove Success of 'One Country, Two Systems' by Facts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- "The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) will prove by facts
that the concept of 'one country, two systems' can make a
success," said Michael Suen Ming-yeung, who took the office of
Secretary for Electoral Affairs of the HKSAR government today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua recently, the 53-year-old
Suen repeatedly stressed that the key to Hong Kong's long-term
prosperity and stability lies in the full implementation of the
principle of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" with a high degree of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Temporarily seconded to the HKSAR Chief Executive's Office in
March, Suen participated in the preparatory work for the formation
of the HKSAR government, which was sworn in on July 1 when China
resumed the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"This was a rare episode in my life," Suen said of his
experience in the past several months with excitement. "Hong
Kong's return to the motherland is a momentous historic event, and
it's a great honor and pride to get involved in it and contribute
my share."
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that over the past four weeks since the
establishment of the HKSAR, business has been as usual in the
local community.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing has changed in Hong Kong except that the Union Jack
and the Hong Kong flag were replaced by the Chinese national flag
and the regional flag of the HKSAR," he noted. "We can see that
the concept of 'one country, two systems' initiated by Mr. Deng
Xiaoping is being carried out."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese central government has given the HKSAR
government a high degree of autonomy in dealing with the SAR's
internal affairs and this reflects the central government's full
confidence in the capabilities of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have also seen that the SAR government, shortly after
its establishment, has begun to handle a number of very important
yet difficult problems, making a good start for the operation of
the SAR," he added.
</P>
<P>
When the Sino-British Joint Declaration was signed in 1984, he
recalled, some people thought Hong Kong's economy was doomed and
they emigrated overseas.
</P>
<P>
Now that Hong Kong continues to enjoy social stability and
economic prosperity, he said, many former emigrants have come back
along with an increasing number of foreign investors, and local
people have gained much more confidence in the future after seeing
that they can continue to have anything they had before the
handover.
</P>
<P>
"This is just like what an ancient saying goes: facts speak
louder than eloquence," he commented.
</P>
<P>
Conceding that there are now still some people in the foreign
media that remain doubtful about the implementation of "one
country, two systems" in Hong Kong, he said that it is unnecessary
to give them an explanation.
</P>
<P>
"Just let them come back to Hong Kong in one year's time, and
facts will speak for us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, a major task for the HKSAR government in
the coming period is to prove by facts to the whole world that the
goal of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people governing
Hong Kong" with a high degree of autonomy can be achieved and will
serve as the most fundamental factor in maintaining Hong Kong's
long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Chinese State Council announced appointments and
removals of some of the principal officials of the HKSAR, among
whom Suen was transferred from Secretary of Home Affairs to
Secretary for Electoral Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Suen said there should be no difficulty for him to do the new
job well as he worked as secretary for constitutional affairs (the
predecessor of secretary for electoral affairs) in charge of
electoral work from 1989 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he also had experience in electoral affairs when
he was seconded to the Chief Executive's Office. Therefore, the
on-going preparatory work for the election of the first
Legislative Council of the SAR is a familiar job for him.
</P>
<P>
According to Suen, the major work of the Department for Home
Affairs includes safeguarding Hong Kong citizens' rights granted
by the HKSAR Basic Law, serving as a channel of communication
between the government and the public, helping formulate relevant
information policies and encouraging local residents'
participation in public affairs.
</P>
<P>
Talking about his new job, Suen said he will try his best to do
it well. He said that the coming election of the first Legislative
Council is the first election of the SAR and is crucial to the
implementation of the policies of "one country, two systems" and
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" with a high autonomy.
</P>
<P>
"The election will attract broad attention. People want to see
if the first election of the SAR is open and fair," he said. "It
must be done well, and I believe we can do it well."
</P>
<P>
He said that an important thing for a good election is the
general participation by Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
"More citizens should be mobilized to register as voters and
actively cast their votes. The more people participate, the more
convincing the results will be. The methods of the election must
be open and fair and acceptable to the masses of Hong Kong
citizens," he said.
</P>
<P>
Suen, who joined the civil service after his graduation from
the Hong Kong University in 1966, said that he spent most of his
career in contacting and communicating with the general public.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a principal official of the SAR, what he
considers most is how to better serve the SAR and its citizens.
</P>
<P>
Senior civil servants must have a sense of commitment, for whom
the most important thing is to protect the overall interests of
Hong Kong and make their own contributions to the success of "one
country, two systems" policy in Hong Kong, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Iran Exchange Soldiers' Bodies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Iran today exchanged the
remains of their soldiers killed during the war between the two
countries from 1980 to 1988, Iraq News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held in the Shalajma border region, east of
the Iraqi province of Basra, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The agency did not say how many dead bodies were exchanged. But
an Iranian News Agency report said the remains of 15 Iranian
soldiers and 47 Iraqi soldiers were handed over.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of soldiers' remains was accomplished under a
bilateral agreement signed in Tehran on September 14, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has found the dead bodies of more than 25,000 Iranian
soldiers since the end of the war, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has affirmed that some 20,000 Iraqi prisoners of war are
still detained in Iran, and Iran claims that there are still at
least 5,000 Iranians held in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Exchange of prisoners of war and the remains of the missing
soldiers are still main obstacles to the normalization of
relations between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
