<HEADLINE> US Accused of Dropping Flares over Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has accused the United
States of having sent one of its warplanes to drop an incendiary
flare over an Iraqi city, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"A U.S. warplane dropped at noon on July 26 an incendiary
flare over the Iraqi province of Basra, southern Iraq," Iraqi
newspaper Al-Thawrah said.
</P>
<P>
"The incendiary flare dropped on a resident's house in the
Hussein district, a residential district in the city of Basra,"
the paper added.
</P>
<P>
It said the dropping of the flare resulted in no casualties,
but it failed to say how much damage the Iraqi resident's house
suffered.
</P>
<P>
An unidentified warplane dropped incendiary flares over the
Diyala province, eastern Iraq, last month. Iraq called it an
enemy warplane, but failed to accuse any country of having
carried out this operation.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its western allies patrol a no-fly zone
in northern Iraq to protect the Kurdish population from attacks
by Iraqi army. 
</P>
