<HEADLINE> Russian Ballerina to Make Debut in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian ballerina Nina
Ananiashvili is expected to radiate confidence and exhibit her
technical virtuousity in tomorrow night's China debut.
</P>
<P>
Nina Ananiashvili and International Stars Co., a troupe with
some of the world's top ballet dancers, will present a lucky
Beijing audience with a performance featuring classical beauty and
dazzling pyrotechnics in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The company's 10 members have enjoyed great fame with their own
troupes, many of which have been in existence for over 200 years.
</P>
<P>
Frank Anderson, former director of the Royal Danish Ballet,
serves as the company's artistic director.
</P>
<P>
"This is our first performance in Beijing," said
Anderson. "Members of the company come from the world's best
ballet troupes."
</P>
<P>
Beijing is the fifth stop on a performance tour which has taken
the company to Japan, Europe, Scandinavia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to Anderson, "Ananiashvili conceived the idea and
selected dancers for International Stars Co. in 1991."
</P>
<P>
Ananiashvili, 34, has strived for excellence and has constantly
refined her dance interpretations. The ballerina offers audiences
a quality of completeness, excellent role interpretation and
exquisite ballet movements in her presentations featuring pure
Russian classicism.
</P>
<P>
Western dance critics have praised Ananiashvili as the greatest
ballerina in today's bullet world.
</P>
<P>
Ananiashvili joined the Moscow Bolshoi Ballet (Moscow Great
Theater Ballet Company) at the age of 17 and starred in Hamburg
performance of "Swan Lake." The German audience honored her
excellent performance of the little swan with a resounding round
of applause lasting well over 30 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
