<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. UPS Workers on Strike in Wage Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 185,000 members of
the Teamsters union of the United States went on strike Sunday
night against United Parcel Service (UPS) that will disrupt
deliveries of documents and packages across the nation.
</P>
<P>
The walkout, followed the collapse of last-ditch negotiations
Sunday night in Washington, was the first nationwide strike in the
90-year history of UPS, which delivers 12 million parcels and
documents a day.
</P>
<P>
UPS estimated that a scattered, one-day walkout in 1994 cost it
50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We will do whatever we can using our management and other
nonunion people to operate to the extent that we can," UPS
spokesman Ken Sternad said.
</P>
<P>
The Atlanta-based company, which has 302,000 employees in the
United States, will make medical and pharmaceutical supplies and
other emergency deliveries its first priority, and also expects to
keep up its international service, Sternad said.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Pilots Association, which represents UPS' 2,000
pilots, said it would honor the Teamsters picket lines.
</P>
<P>
As UPS takes 80 percent of the nation's parcel market, its
competitors wouldn't be able to take up the industry giant's
entire load.
</P>
<P>
The rival Federal Express Corp. had already reported a sharp
increase in business in recent days, and imposed limits including
cutting drop-off times by two hours, suspending money-back
guarantees and declining new regular accounts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Postal Service announced temporary measures today,
including limiting customers to four parcels a visit. Postmaster
General Marvin Runyon said "an extraordinary increase in volume"
was expected.
</P>
<P>
In the dispute, the Teamsters want the company to create more
full-time jobs for its part-time workers, eliminate the use of
outside contractors, increase wages and improve pension benefits
and job safety.
</P>
<P>
UPS has offered to create 1,000 full-time jobs over the life of
a proposed five-year contract, for which part-timers would be
given first preference. The proposed contract would increase top
hourly pay for full-time workers by 1.5 dollars to 21.45 dollars
and the hourly wage for the lowest paid part-time employees three
dollars to 11 dollars by 2001.
</P>
<P>
UPS also want to replace the Teamsters pension program with one
of its own, the payout of which would be 50 percent higher than
the program now available. The company's plan would pay retirees
100 dollars a month for every year of service up to 3,500 a month.
</P>
<P>
But union officials said the UPS proposal were inadequate for a
company in which 57 percent of its work force is made up of
part-time workers and the latter do the same work as full-timers
but earn less. Union officials also said that the UPS pension
program was a deal killer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Soldiers' Remains Returned by DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The remains of four U.S. soldiers
killed in the Korean War were handed over to the U.S. army
stationed in South Korea on Monday at the truce village of
Panmunjom by the Korean People's Army.
</P>
<P>
The new commander of the 8th U.S. Army, Lt. Gen. Randolph
W. House, and an official from the U.S. Defense Department
attended the handover ceremony at the village on the border
between South Korea and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The remains were unearthed last month by a U.S. excavation team
visiting Unsan County, in the DPRK's North Pyongan Province, some
30 kilometers from the Chinese border, according to the
U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
Unsan County was the scene of fierce fighting during the
1950-53 Korean War, claiming the lives of about 350 U.S. soldiers
in October 1950.
</P>
<P>
There have been three excavation missions to recover the
remains of U.S. soldiers this year following an agreement between
the United States and the DPRK. The DPRK handed over the remains
of 210 U.S. soldiers between 1990 and 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
