<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices Seen to Increase in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen believe that prices
will increase next month in the Philippines should the
depreciation of the country's currency peso and higher interest
rates continue in the ensuing months.
</P>
<P>
Industrialist Raul Concepcion told reporters that August is a
crucial month because unless the Philippine Central Bank can
reverse the trend, "everything will go up next month."
</P>
<P>
Concepcion, who is chairman of the Consumer and Oil Price
Watch, said manufacturers will be forced to scale down their
production and prices will go up as their inventory levels at old
prices will be exhausted.
</P>
<P>
With higher prices due to these factors and the recent oil
price hike, he said, the labor sector will then start clamoring
for a new round of wage adjustments.
</P>
<P>
A special committee, composed of officials from the departments
of energy and trade and industry, will be tasked to monitor the
prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
According to Concepcion, the country's business circle has
asked the central bank to help stabilize the peso by taking the
following measures:
</P>
<P>
-- compel exporters to surrender their export proceeds within
30 days from receipt of proceeds;
</P>
<P>
-- business and industry should be allowed to purchase foreign
exchange only for the payment of current maturing foreign debt and
not hedge for the future; and
</P>
<P>
-- priority on the sale of foreign exchange should be given to
import and export trade-related transactions over remittance of
dividends, profits and invisibles.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank was forced to allow the peso to
float on July 11 due to massive attacks by currency speculators
who shifted to the peso after the July 2 depreciation of the Thai
baht.
</P>
<P>
The peso has so far fallen nearly 10 percent in its value since
its de facto depreciation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
