<HEADLINE> Solana Urges Western Aid to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana today urged the Western nations to provide assistance to
Russia as the country is poised for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who arrived here Sunday on a private visit, praised
Russia's economic reforms during his meeting today with First
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Nemtsov told reporters that he had
reiterated Russian opposition to NATO's eastward expansion,
including the incorporation of the three Baltic states into the
Western military alliance. Russia has threatened to revoke its
recent pact with NATO if that happens.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia seeks stronger economic ties with western
Europe and supports a single European market, although Moscow
remains opposed to anti-dumping measures against some Russian
products announced by the European Union last week, he said.
</P>
<P>
Presently, Russian trade volume with the European Union
accounts for 40 percent of its total foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that the anti-dumping measures would cost
Russia one billion U.S. dollars a year if implemented. 
</P>
