<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agro Research Body Flays Nigeria's Wheat Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural scientists in Nigeria
have decried the import of wheat, saying that close substitutes
of the produce are in abundant supply in the country.
</P>
<P>
The International Institute of Tropical Agriculture (IITA), a
United Nations-related organ based in western Nigeria, said it
had significant breakthroughs in the production of cassava,
maize, cowpea and soybean, among others.
</P>
<P>
However, the federal government has continued to import an
estimated 100 million tons or more wheat every year.
</P>
<P>
Celebrating its 30th anniversary two weeks ago, IITA announced
it had developed a "super cassava" variety with an output of 40
tons per hectare, tripling the yield of the current varieties.
</P>
<P>
Cassava is most common at the dinner table of Nigerians. IITA
has developed many products derivative from cassava, including
bread, cookies, doughnut, strips and noodles. Many of the
products are being consumed by Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
The products, according to IITA's Head of Biochemistry
Department Mpoko Bokanga, are of the same quality with those made
from wheat.
</P>
<P>
But the importation of wheat has been posing serious threat to
the local market.
</P>
<P>
As the country's present capacity is already enhanced to
produce more than 30 million tons of cassava annually, it is high
time the government discouraged wheat import, he added.
</P>
<P>
IITA Director General Lucas Brader shared the same view,
saying that virtually all the maize grown now in the country was
resistant to the disease which used to cause an average of 10
percent loss per year.
</P>
<P>
This research development will make more maize available for
use as alternative to wheat, he said.
</P>
<P>
"At least an extra two million tons of maize is produced
yearly, which means an annual saving of 300 to 400 million
dollars, enough to feed 10 million people," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Needs New Internal Balance, Singapore Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The expansion of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) to include Laos and
Myanmar means that the regional group needs to find a new internal
equilibrium, Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"If ASEAN maintains its record of playing a role in
contributing to peace and stability in the region, ASEAN's
standing in the international community will be enhanced. It will
also increase the influence and bargaining power of ASEAN
vis-a-vis other states and regional groups," the foreign minister
said in his keynote address at the two-day ASEAN Roundtable 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The key message I wish to leave at this Roundtable is that we
cannot take for granted that ASEAN will succeed. ASEAN faces many
serious challenges in the years ahead," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
One of the challenges that ASEAN faces, he said, is whether
ASEAN can retain the close knit and almost "telepathic"
understanding it has built up over the last 30 years, or in other
words, whether ASEAN's detractors are right in saying that a
"two-tier" ASEAN will develop.
</P>
<P>
Another concern, he said, is that whether an enlarged ASEAN can
continue to forge consensus on key international issues, or
whether ASEAN's cohesiveness will fray.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister also underlined what he called "a unique
challenge" that has been posed by the entry of Myanmar. He noted
that the European Union says it cannot cooperate with Myanmar,
while ASEAN on its part has said that dialogue partners should not
discriminate among ASEAN member states in development assistance.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the outlook for ASEAN, which marked its 30th
anniversary this year, continues to remain bright, but much work
remains to be done, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, which admitted Vietnam in July 1995, was again expanded
last month with Laos and Myanmar joining in. Apart from these
three new members, ASEAN also includes Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Thailand, Singapore, and Brunei.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
