<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Iran's New President Khatami Sworn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Mohammad Khatami, a liberal
clergyman, was sworn in here today as Iran's new president before
a conservative-dominated parliament which may paralyze his
presidency for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Khatami who will take Iran to the 21st century will have
his first fight with the Parliament over the choice of his
ministers. The new president would introduce his cabinet to the
parliament on August 9 and 10.
</P>
<P>
Despite many speculations in the Iranian press about who will
serve in Khatami's government, so far Khatami has kept the choices
to himself and has not made any public announcement except Hassan
Habibi, who was appointed his first vice-president today.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Khatami would have a hard time gaining
the Parliament's approval for important ministries such as
defense, information, foreign affairs, interior and culture.
</P>
<P>
This is because the rightist camp headed by Khatami's rival
Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri controls about 150
seats of the 270-seat Parliament while Khatami's supporters from
the moderate camp and leftist group only enjoys a minority of
about 110 seats in the legislative body.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, these key posts such as interior minister
and foreign minister have been usually directly controlled by
Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei. But, Khatami seems to
challenge Khamenei and try to change the pattern by stressing the
rule of law.
</P>
<P>
Khatami won by a landslide victory on May 23, gaining
over 20 million votes and defeating his arch rival conservative
Parliament Speaker Nateq-Nouri who received only 7 million votes.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's victory came as a jolt to the conservative camp
who considered Nateq-Nouri a front-runner early in the race.
</P>
<P>
"The bitter defeat has made the conservative camp truly
determined to get back at Khatami at every step," one local
observer told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
But Khatami's problems are not limited to the Parliament.
Problems of unemployment, high inflation, economic stagnation,
civil liberties, strained relations with the west and some
neighbors and other issues are all challenging for Khatami who can
only maneuver within the framework of the give-and-take formula
set by the supreme leader Khamenei despite the powerful mandate
given by the 20 million plus voters.
</P>
<P>
If Khatami clashes with Khamenei, the Parliament which goes
along with Khamenei's directive can impeach Khatami. Khatami may
then become the second Iranian president which would be ousted
by a decree from the supreme leader.
</P>
<P>
"I do not want to be in Mr. Khatami's shoes. He has to walk a
tightrope, if he compromises too much with the Leader and the
conservative camp, then he has forgotten his campaign promises to
the nation," an editor at a Persian daily said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"If he insists on his mandate for change, he might end up in
the same manner that Bani Sadr did," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran's first president . Bani Sadr was ousted in June 1981 for
clashing with the founder of the Islamic Republic of Iran
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. He later fled the country and is now
an outspoken critic of Tehran's government in exile in
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's Cocoa Production Expected to Up 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Global leading cocoa grower and
exporter Ghana is expected to produce 350,000 tons of cocoa in the
1997-1998 season, an increase of 17.1 percent from the last season.
</P>
<P>
Cocoa export in the period is also projected to be more than that
in the last season to about 350,000 tons. Foreign exchange earning
from the export of cocoa is estimated at 57 million U.S. dollars, next
only to the 580 million dollars from that of gold, said a
report from Accra reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-1997 production season, Ghana exported 338,000 tons of
cocoa, a hefty increase of 43 percent over the previous season.
</P>
<P>
Cocoa is Ghana's traditional export product which earns more than
30 percent of the country's export revenue.
</P>
<P>
To further encourage cocoa production, the Ghanaian government
recently offered growers a 50-percent increase in cocao purchasing
price, from 590 dollars per ton to 885 dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
