<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Softens Charges Against PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu today repeated his charges against the Palestinian
National Authority with regard to fighting terrorism, but in a
softened tone.
</P>
<P>
While accusing the PNA of having done nothing to break up the
Hamas and Islamic Jihad infrastructure in the autonomous areas,
Netanyahu admited that Israel still does not know the origin of
the two suicide bombers in last week's Jerusalem market blasts
which killed 15 people, including themselves.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu apparently realized that he had gone a bit too far in
lashing out at his peace partner because of the fact that it had
proved wrong to jump to the conclusion that the two terrorists
were from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
A furious Netanyahu had harshly attacked the PNA following the
bombing attack, saying that the Palestinian self-rule government
had done nothing against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Having softened his tone, however, Netanyahu insisted that it
is likely that the terrorists were aided by residents of the
(Palestinian) territories.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that the PNA must decide if it wants to be a
regime that gives shelter to terrorists, like Iraq or Iran, or
wants to be a government combating terrorist like Egypt and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks when he was speaking with the
visiting U.S. Republican Senator Phil Gramm. In response to a
reporter's question later, Netanyahu denied that he was opposed to
a pending visit by President Ezer Weizman to Washington.
</P>
<P>
He said that was surprised to read this morning the Ha'aretz
newspaper report that he objected to the U.S. invitation to
Weizman, a move regarded here as a sign of President Bill
Clinton's unhappiness about the premier's hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said this morning that he has not yet decided whether
he is going, but declared that no one would tell him what to
do. 
</P>
