<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life in HK Back to Normal After Typhoon Victor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Life is gradually returning to
normal after Hong Kong was hit Saturday by the worst typhoon in 14
years.
</P>
<P>
Typhoon Victor moved away from Hong Kong early Sunday morning
before killing one person and injuring at least 55.
</P>
<P>
The first typhoon of the season, which packed winds of between
110 and 120 kilometers per hour, was centered over Hong Kong
Saturday night and it moved northward into South China's Guangdong
province at 03:30 Sunday, according to Hong Kong Observatory.
</P>
<P>
The No. 9 Typhoon Signal was raised Saturday afternoon, the
first time since 1983. It was lowered to No. 8 shortly before
midnight after Victor was weakening into a severe topical storm.
The No. 8 signal was lowered early Sunday morning, replaced by the
No. 3 Strong Wind Signal.
</P>
<P>
A 44-year-old British engineer drowned off Stanley beach when
he dived into two-meter-deep waves to try to rescue two students
who were washed into the sea during the peak of the storm. The
two were later pulled by police rescuers to safety from the rough
seas.
</P>
<P>
At least 55 people were reported injured but most were treated
in hospital for minor injuries and released.
</P>
<P>
In a similar case 14 years ago, Typhoon Ellen killed 10 people
and injured over 300 others.
</P>
<P>
Local transport services such as buses, ferries, trams, Mass
Transit Railway, planes and taxis which were brought to a virtual
standstill late Saturday and early Sunday, were resumed later
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Passengers stranded at the Kai Tak Airport due to 320 flights
delayed, canceled or diverted to nearby airports, took alternative
flights Sunday or Monday. Some 9,000 people were estimated at the
airport at the height of the tempest.
</P>
<P>
Some of the flights were ordered to keep flying for up to two
hours before landing at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Most of the roads which were closed due to landslides, fallen
trees and construction scaffoldings, have been opened to traffic.
</P>
<P>
But traffic congestion is likely to persist for a few more
days. A road in Cheung Sha Wan was blocked by a landslide, which
dumped some 1,000 cubic meters of mud and almost buried a taxi
passing by. A total of 14 landslides were reported Sunday after
the pouring rain across the region, registered at about 400
millimeters.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was directly hit by a typhoon for the third time in
history.
</P>
<P>
But weather watchers have predicted the region was still under
the influence of Victor's outer rain bands, with moderate winds
and cloudy skies with occasional showers to come in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
Residents can also feel the affects. Vegetable prices are
about 10 percent higher because the typhoon has destroyed
half of the local production. Farmers are trying to fetch
whatever they can from the flood water to meet the market
demands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
