<HEADLINE> AlliedSignal Targets Growing Air Industry in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- AlliedSignal Aerospace, one of
the world's leading suppliers of aircraft components, is making
inroads into the fast-growing Asia-Pacific region to capture a
significant share of the booming aerospace business.
</P>
<P>
Dan Burnham, president of AlliedSignal Aerospace, said here
today: "The anticipated growth rate in air travel in this corner
of the world is spurring a wealth of new aerospace component and
service opportunities."
</P>
<P>
As much as 40 percent of the world's new civil jetliner sales
between now and 2013 could be destined for the airlines in the
Asia-Pacific region, he quoted Boeing projections as saying.
</P>
<P>
In particular, he focused on the AlliedSignal's presence in
China, whose growing air travel industry could account for 70
billion US dollars worth of new commercial aircraft during the
next two decades.
</P>
<P>
Burnham said that his company is taking steps to ensure its
success in winning a share of this huge and thriving market. It
has initiated Human Resources programs to train local staff, and
built repair, overhaul and manufacturing facilities in cooperation
with local partners.
</P>
<P>
AlliedSignal Aerospace has set up joint ventures in Xiamen and
Shanghai to provide aircraft component repair and overhaul
services. More ventures are under negotiation to develop and
manufacture aircraft control systems.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to position ourselves as an integral part of local
industry, not simply a distant global aerospace player," said
Burnham.
</P>
<P>
AlliedSignal Aerospace signed a contract here today with the
Hong Kong government to supply an advanced surveillance radar,
called Precision Runway Monitor system, to the double-runway New
Airport now under construction at Chek Lap Kok and scheduled to
open its first runway in April 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
