<HEADLINE> Advanced Radar System to Be Installed at New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- An updated radar system, which
can keep a close eye on flights that make simultaneous parallel
approaches to multiple runways, will be installed at the New
Airport, now under construction at Chek Lap Kok, an outlying
island in the west of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Precision Runway Monitor (PRM) system will be supplied by
AlliedSignal Aerospace under a contract signed here today between
the U.S.-based company and the Hong Kong government.
</P>
<P>
Scanning five times faster than the conventional surveillance
radar, the new system tracks and displays each aircraft, updates
position and velocity of approaching flights at the rate of once
per second.
</P>
<P>
Claimed to be the only fully certified radar system for
parallel runway approaches, the system is able to help increase
airport capacity, improve safety and lower operating costs by
reducing aircraft delays.
</P>
<P>
Dan Burnham, president of AlliedSignal Aerospace, told a news
briefing here today: "The PRM system will play a key role in
helping Hong Kong's new airport become one of the major hubs in
Asia."
</P>
<P>
To have the whole system built in Hong Kong, including staff
training and simulators, will cost 13 million U.S. dollars. A
technician from AlliedSignal Aerospace said that the system is
cost effective at large international airports with a huge flow of
passengers and closely-spaced runways.
</P>
<P>
AlliedSigal Aerospace will start to install the PRM system at
Chek Lap Lok in the first quarter of 1999 and complete the work by
the end of year, when the second runway will go into operation.
The first runway is expected to open in April, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The PRM system has been set up at airports in Minneapolis-St.
Paul in the United States and Sydney, Australia. Four more have
been planned for airports in New York, St. Louis, Philadelphia and
Atlanta in the U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
