<HEADLINE> Kenyan Government Declared August 8 National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Labour Minister Philip
Masinde has declared illegal this Friday's general strike due to
be called by the opposition National Convention Executive Council
(NCEC), local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
On a fund-raising occasion Sunday in Busia, western Kenya, the
minister warned that the government would not protect workers who
may lose their jobs as a result of participating in the strike.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide strike has been designed to speed up the
constitutional reform process.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC issued a five-day ultimatum on August 2 to the
government, urging the government to show seriousness over the
reform issue or face the strike.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Environment Minister Henry Kosgey noted
that the issue of constitutional reform should not be hijacked by
self-appointed leaders.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's parliament is "the only place" where the matter could
be handled, the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here on Sunday, 10 trade unions accused
the NCEC of hijacking the labour movement in the country by
calling for a strike.
</P>
<P>
The trade unions affiliated to the Central Organization of
Trade Unions of Kenya said in a statement that strikes was a
function of trade unions and not of political parties.
</P>
<P>
Officials of trade unions called on workers, leaders and the
labour movement to shun the strike and warned the NCEC to stop
inciting workers against their employers and the government.
</P>
</TEXT>
