<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Anti-Triad Law Comes Into Effect in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A new law aiming to fight against
organized crimes more effectively went into effect today,
following a recent wave of violence that wounded three.
</P>
<P>
Passed last month by the Macao Legislative Assembly after
several weeks of consultation with local communities and
government departments, the law is said to have given the security
forces and the judiciary more power in combatting crimes.
</P>
<P>
The new law has 42 articles, describing in detail 21 kinds of
activities that constitute "organized crimes." They include
homicide, abduction, smuggling of population, forcing others as
prostitutes, aiding illegal immigration, illegally trading, and
making, using, carrying, and smuggling of arms.
</P>
<P>
The law also permits police to have broader power of
investigating and evidence gathering. Under the new law, the
courts will be able to deal more promptly with suspected crimes and
police forces can use "infiltrated agents."
</P>
<P>
The law states that those who are found to have initiated a
triad will be sentenced to between five to 12 years in
imprisonment, and leading members of underground society will also
get up to 12 years behind bars.
</P>
<P>
The new law is based on a previous anti-organized crimes act,
which over the past several years had failed in curtailing such
activities.
</P>
<P>
Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira said last week that the new
legislation "shows the determination of the government to combat
activities of criminal gangs."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a commentary in today's "Macao Daily News" urged the
authorities to take effective measures to rectify the security
forces, and to eradicate infiltrated "triad elements."
</P>
<P>
It also said that the new law must be implemented to the
letter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Train Accident Injures 13 in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen passengers, including
a minister of state, was injured when 11 coaches of a New
Delhi-bound express train derailed near a station which is about
135 kilometers away from the capital this morning, Press Trust of
India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The derailment, which occurred at around 02:45 hours local time
this morning, is suspected due to sabotage as the rail joints were
found open and fishplates were found lying inside the tracks at
the site of derailment, railway sources said.
</P>
<P>
The injured, including four army personnel who were stated to
be in serious condition, were rushed to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of State for Water Resources Sheesh Ram Ola,
who sustained minor injuries during the accident, returned to the
capital after receiving first aid.
</P>
<P>
Rail traffic in the Delhi-Haryana-Rajasthan section, which has
been disrupted following the accident, would be restored by early
tomorrow morning, according to the railway sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
