<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Coal Export Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will have more
profit from coal export this year due to higher tonnages exported
to India and the first-time exports to Indonesia and the
Philippines, according to a report issued by South Africa Coal
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The report said South Africa's exports of coal fell last year
after a loss of market share in the Far East. It also attributed
the decline to domestic problems, such as high seasonal rainfalls
at the beginning of last year and freight bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's coal output last year was about 261.5 million
tons, of which about 206 million tons were saleable within the
country and 60 million tons exported, according to the local
Mineral Bureau.
</P>
<P>
While Indian markets grow, the traditionally strong European
Union market is expected to shrink 3.4 million tons to 134
million this year, the report quoted European Commission
statistics as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Despite the higher coal export, South African coal producers,
the Mineral Bureau said, would have to fight to maintain their
market share.
</P>
<P>
"Should promises of increased production and exports of
low-cost coal from new producers in Colombia, Indonesia and
Venezuela materialize, South African exporters will struggle to
maintain or increase their share of the market," the bureau said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
