<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Direct Phone Service Opens between Two Koreas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Inter-Korean direct phone lines
opened this afternoon linking Seoul with Shinpo, the nuclear
reactor construction site in Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The eight telephone lines, four for private use and the other
for official purposes, connected the two Koreas as the first time
after the peninsula was divided for more than 50 years, the Yonhap
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The lines were opened to enable South Korean workers and
officials who have been dispatched to Shinpo for the reactor
project to discuss official matters with the (South) Korea
Electric Power Corporation, the main contractor of the project,
and to talk privately with their family members in the South.
</P>
<P>
The Korean Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO), an
international consortium formed by the U.S., South Korea and
Japan, is in charge of building two light water reactors for DPRK,
under a DPRK-U.S. agreement.
</P>
<P>
The opening of direct communication lines symbolizes the de
facto launch of the project, said the Yonhap.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is ready to open international direct dialing
service with DPRK through fiber optic cable and Intelsat whenever
it is needed, said an official of the South Korea
Telecommunication Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
