<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afro-beat King Dies of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian popular musician Fela
Anikulapo-Kuti, known as the Afro-beat King, died of
complications of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS), his
family announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement made by his elder brother Olikoye Ransome-Kuti
said that he died at around 5:30 P.M. on Sunday in a hospital in
Lagos.
</P>
<P>
"The immediate cause of death is heart failure but he had many
complications arising from Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome
(AIDS)," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Fela is the first prominent Nigerian known to have died of
AIDs, though the country's AIDS/HIV population is estimated to be
as high as two million.
</P>
<P>
Fela had been ill for a long time before his death at the age
of 59.
</P>
<P>
He was born on October 15, 1938. He formed his first band in
1959 in London, where he was attending the Trinity College of
Music in Oxford from 1959 to 1962.
</P>
<P>
Fela leaves behind him over 40 music albums. Known as the
Afrobeat king, he is the most popular musician in Nigeria and his
influence went beyond his own country.
</P>
<P>
Most of his works are believed to have political undertones
which led to his strained relations with the authority.
</P>
<P>
His private life is most controversial. He was reportedly
married to 27 wives and is known to be using Indian hemp for
which his home was raided by the police for two times, the second
time just several months ago.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
