<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Enterprises Urged to Adapt to Regional Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-scale
enterprises (SMEs) in Southeast Asia have been urged to adapt to
the regional dynamics and changes and avail themselves of the
benefits of the larger ASEAN market.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian International Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah
Aziz said at the opening of the ASEAN-SMI showcase here today that
ASEAN industrial cooperation is expected to be strengthened and
provide opportunities for resource pooling among industrial
establishments in ASEAN (Association of Southeast Nations).
</P>
<P>
SMEs, which constitute about 80 percent of the total
establishments in the individual domestic economies, should
however build up the necessary capacities and capabilities to
enhance the inter- and intra-industry linkages both at home and
regionally, she said.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah urged the SMEs to invest in process and product
innovation and place priority on research and development and move
on to higher planes of technological development and application.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the SMEs in the region must begin to
establish an ASEAN and East Asian SME Network in order to optimize
benefits that they can derive from various regional initiatives
and programs, particularly in industrial development.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the realization of the ASEAN Investment Area
concept will further induce investment flows into ASEAN as well as
intra-ASEAN investment cross-flows.
</P>
<P>
She was of the view that the dismantling of both tariff and
non-tariff barriers in markets elsewhere can provide new
opportunities for SMEs, provided they have the requisite
preparedness to compete in the export market.
</P>
<P>
It is projected that in the year 2003 some 88 percent of
products under the Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT)
scheme, the implementation mechanism of the ASEAN Free Trade Area
(AFTA), will be at tariff lines of five percent or below, Rafidah
said.
</P>
<P>
Forty-one percent of the CEPT products is expected to be at
zero duty, eight percent at three percent tariff and 47 percent at
five percent tariff level, the minister said, adding that by the
year 2000 the average rate of ASEAN CEPT for the top five sectors
will be between zero and five percent.
</P>
<P>
The sectors include machinery and electrical appliances,
mineral products, base metals, textiles and chemicals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
