<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 08:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Sworn in as Fifth President of Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's moderate cleric Mohammad
Khatami, 54, was sworn in here today as the fifth president of the
Islamic Republic of Iran since its founding in 1979.
</P>
<P>
In his swearing-in ceremony at the Majlis (parliament), the new
Iranian president attempted to offer a softer image of his country
by calling for dialogues with other countries.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said at the ceremony, present in which were his
predecessor President Hashemi Rafsanjani and some 600 ministers,
high-ranking officials and foreign diplomats, that Iran would not
seek to initiate tension in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The government considers the dialogue between the
civilizations a necessity and would try to avoid creating
tension," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he assured the hardliners at home that he was
committed to the ideal of radical Islam.
</P>
<P>
"We want to defend the Moslems around the world, especially
the Palestinian nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who entered the presidential race on a liberal
platform, said that he would fight for freedom and individual
rights.
</P>
<P>
"I have sworn on the Holy Koran and before you that ... I will
support the freedom and the rights of the individuals," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The best thing that the Executive Branch can do at this
juncture would be to try to institutionalize the law and most
importantly the constitution in order to serve the people," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The relatively liberal president also vowed to fight for a
balanced economy in which poverty would be absent.
</P>
<P>
"Elimination of the scourge of poverty is among the
responsibilities of the Islamic Republic of Iran," Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who served as Iran's minister of culture between 1982
and 1992, called on intellectuals and the press to evaluate and
critique his performance during his tenure which ends in 2001.
</P>
<P>
"I ask the press, the academe and people of culture ... to
increase public participation in the decision-making process by
their continuous evaluation and critique," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new president, who was elected by a landslide victory
after gaining nearly 70 percent of the votes on May 23, said that
the people were the main asset of the Islamic system in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The massive popular support for Khatami came as a surprise to
many, including those in the well-established and powerful
conservative camp here. His arch challenger, hardline Parliament
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri, who was considered a front-runner
at the early stage of the race, suffered a humiliating defeat by
collecting some 25 of the ballots.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony today, Nateq-Nouri vowed that the parliament
would try its best to help Khatami's government to start its
work.
</P>
<P>
"We the parliamentarians have a religious and legal duty to
... help the new government start its work," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, it is widely believed here that the hardliner-dominated
parliament will this majority to interfere in the new president's
administration, first of all, the formation of his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has so far refused to discuss his choice of ministers
with the parliament. Reports here said he will introduce his
cabinet members to the parliament on August 9 and 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
