<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Launches World's First HIV Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia formally launched
today the world's first experiment which offers enormous hope in
the fight against AIDS and other serious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Science and Technology Minister Peter
McGauran said the experiment, the world's first of its kind,
involves human trials of the revolutionary "gene shears"
technology, as a potential treatment of HIV, which causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Gene shears, or ribozymes, are naturally-occurring enzymes
which are capable of "switching off" specific genes. Test-tube
trials have already proven it can be used to prevent replication
of HIV.
</P>
<P>
The human trials, which will be undertaken in two stages, at
St. Vincent's Hospital, Sydney, and at a hospital in Los Angeles,
USA, will determine the safety and ability of gene shears in
destroying HIV in infected patients.
</P>
<P>
The experiment will involve six sets of identical twins. One of
each pair is HIV-positive and will receive white blood cells,
equipped with the anti-HIV gene shear, from the uninfected twin.
In the second stage, the infected twin will be infused with bone
marrow engineered with the gene shear.
</P>
<P>
"Gene shears have been acclaimed by the international
scientific community as one of the most significant breakthroughs
in molecular biology this decade, with suggestions it could be on
a par with the discovery of penicillin," McGauran said.
</P>
<P>
"Its potential applications are enormous, particularly in the
area of human health, but also in food and animal industries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The technology will be tested against a range of other human
diseases over the next three years. Field trials into
virus-resistant vegetable crops are already well-advanced.
</P>
<P>
McGauran said gene shears are also proof of the importance of
basic science.
</P>
<P>
The technology was first patented in 1987 by the Commonwealth
Scientific and Industrial Research Organization, Australia's
leading research body, and has been further developed through the
establishment of Gene Shears Pty Ltd. and in partnership with
pharmaceutical giant Johnson and Johnson.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
