<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Enterprises Open Businesses Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Township enterprises in
China's Zhejiang Province have been trying their luck overseas
after they have faced more competition on the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
By now, township enterprises in the province have opened
businesses in more than 20 countries and regions, which serve as a
springboard for other township enterprises to enter the
international market.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang is one of the major areas with flourishing township
industry. Last year, 63 percent of its value-added industrial
output and more than half its exports came from township
businesses. And 14 percent of the workers and staff are
professionals who are much better qualified for market competition.
</P>
<P>
Shaoxing County is one example of how this works. In 1993, the
Zhejiang Youlan Group spent 300,000 yuan on a trade company in
Russia, whose textile products now do well on the East European
market. Then, 15 more businesses followed suit and have invested
nearly four million US dollars abroad.
</P>
<P>
Competing globally not only helps township enterprises sell
their products, but also helps them acquire market information and
advanced technology. More than 70 percent of the entities overseas
are showing a profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
