<HEADLINE> Palestinian Man Shot Dead Near Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A 61-year-old Palestinian man
was killed in a overnight shooting near the Jewish settlement of
Karmel, south of Hebron, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian eye witnesses said the man, who was identified as
Issa Misif from the village Yatta, was walking by the roadside
with his flock of sheep, when shots were fired at him from a
passing Israeli car.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces are investigating the death of Misif,
whose body has been taken for autopsy. The initial check
revealed that he was shot twice in the chest by a pistol.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security sources said they did not believe Misif was a
land dealer, nor was he suspected of being a collaborator with
Israel. Land dealers and collaborators are common targets of
terror attacks by Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Some suspected the killing of Misif was a revenge attack
carried out by Jewish settlers in retaliation for the Wednesday
twin suicide bombings in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, which
killed 15 people and wounded 170 others. The militant
anti-Israeli Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) has claimed
responsibility for the attack, though Israel remains dubious
about the authenticity of the claim.
</P>
<P>
"We assume it was a revenge killing by settlers for the attack
in Jerusalem last week. People are very angry, but no everybody
knows about it yet," said Ahmed Abu Kbeida, a resident from
Yatta.
</P>
<P>
But Opher Sivan, spokesman for Israeli police in West Bank,
cautioned against speculation about the identity of the killers,
saying "everything claimed in the media is pure speculation at
this point."
</P>
<P>
Following the Wednesday bombings, Israeli security forces have
been keeping high alert across the country amid intelligence
warnings about new terror attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
