<HEADLINE> New Project For Chinese Aircraft-Repair Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Its successful business has
encouraged a joint venture aircraft-repair company in Xiamen City
in China's Fujian Province to start building a new airplane hanger
a mere 18 months after the completion of its first one.
</P>
<P>
The Taikoo (Xiamen) Aircraft Engineering Co. Ltd., which was
jointly set up by six domestic and overseas companies in January
of 1996, is in the business of maintenance and overhaul work on
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Its first hanger, which cost 63 million US dollars, can hold
three long-range passenger airplanes, and the company has done
maintenance and repair work on 26 Boeing-747s and four
Boeing-737s.
</P>
<P>
The second phase project will cost 50.5 million US Dollars and
is scheduled to be completed by 1999, making company the country's
largest aircraft maintenance company. 
