<HEADLINE> Mandela to Mediate Political Crisis in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has invited delegations of the Lesotho government
and opposition parties to meet in Pretoria to solve their
differences, local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The three major opposition parties invited by Mandela, who is
also chairman of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC), are the Basotuland Congress Party (BCP), the Basotho
National Party and the Marematluo Freedom Party, the report
quoted a BCP spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
Robert Mugabe, President of Zimbabwe and Chairman of the
Political and Reconciliation Unit of the SADC, and his Botswanan
counterpart Ketumile Masire who is former chairman of the SADC,
will also be present at the meeting, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho has been embroiled in a political crisis since June 9
when Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle, hitherto leader of BCP, the
majority party in parliament, left the party along with 40
parliamentarians to form the Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
The move by Mokhehle has infuriated opposition parties,
non-governmental organizations and some lawyers in Lesotho, so
much that they termed it as immoral, unlawful and
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
They called on King Letsie to dismiss Mokhehle and even
demanded for free elections.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle, however, defended his action, saying that he was not
wrong as he enjoyed the support of the majority of members of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
So far, King Letsie has not commented on Mokhehle's move.
</P>
</TEXT>
