<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Iran's New President Mohammad Khatami </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Mohammad Khatami, 54, was sworn in
here today as Iran's fifth president to replace 64-year-old
Hashemi Rafsanjani who ran the 62-million populated country for
two consecutive four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
The black turbaned new president was born in Ardakan, in the
central province of Yazd in 1943 to a religious family.
</P>
<P>
Son of an Ayatollah, senior level clergyman in Islam, Khatami
finished his early school years in his homeland. Then he attended
religious science center in Qom, about 140 kilometers south of
capital Tehran, from 1961 before getting his diploma.
</P>
<P>
Several years later, he got his B.A. in philosophy from
Isfahan University, accomplishing religious studies in senior
level at Qom Seminary.
</P>
<P>
Having started his post graduate studies in educational
sciences at Tehran University from 1970, he returned to Qom later
to pursue advanced Islamic courses at Qom seminary.
</P>
<P>
Khatami was involved in political activities and anti-Shah
campaign by preparing, duplicating and distributing political
statements, especially those issued by the late spiritual leader
Ruhollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
He began his political activities at the Association of the
Moslem Students of Isfahan University, worked closely with
Khomeini's late son Ahmad Khomeini and Mohammad Montazeri and
organized religious and political debates.
</P>
<P>
Khatami chaired Islamic center of Hamburg in Germany before
the victory of the 1979 Islamic Revolution. The center turned into
an Islamic campaign center when Khomeini went to France.
</P>
<P>
He represented Ardakan and Meybod constituencies in the first
term of Parliament in 1980 and was appointed as the head of Kayhan
Institute by Khomeini in 1981.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, he was appointed as the minister of culture and
Islamic guidance during the premiership of Hussein Mousavi.
</P>
<P>
During the 1980-88 war between Iran Iraq, he served different
responsibilities including deputy and head of the joint command of
the armed forces and chairman of the war propaganda headquarters.
</P>
<P>
He was again appointed as minister of culture and Islamic
guidance by President Rafsanjani in 1989. But he had to resign
from the post due to pressure from the country's hardline bloc
after being labeled as liberal-minded.
</P>
<P>
Following his resignation in 1992, Khatami was appointed as
cultural advisor to president Rafsanjani and head of the National
Library.
</P>
<P>
He is familiar with three languages of English, German and
Arabic and has written a number of books and articles in
different fields.
</P>
<P>
He got married in 1974 and has two daughters and a son.
</P>
<P>
Khatami was elected as the fifth president by gaining
20,078,178 votes, nearly 70 percent of the votes cast on May
27 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
