<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Clothing Industry Facing Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (xinhua) -- Zimbabwe Clothing Manufacturers'
Association Chairman Steve Bowen said on Sunday that more
companies in the clothing industry would be forced to close this
year because the industry was not doing well.
</P>
<P>
Seven textile companies have been liquidated since January
this year, causing hundreds of job losses, he said, adding 60
other firms are being sued for failing to contribute towards
workers' pensions.
</P>
<P>
The chairman blamed poor business on the high duty imposed on
imported raw materials as well as cheap garments flooding the
market from the Common Market of the Eastern anf Southern Africa
(COMESA) states.
</P>
<P>
Moreover,the 30 percent duty imposed on goods from Zimbabwe by
South Africa was too high and had resulted in only 7,195 garments
out of a quota of three million being exported to South Africa
this year, Bowen added.
</P>
<P>
"Our market has been flooded by imported goods because it is
cheaper to import finished products than raw materials. There is
no incentive for manufacturers and the industry is likely to be
affected by this for a long time," he said.
</P>
<P>
A 30 percent duty was charged on imported raw materials while
those who brought in finished products were charged only 10
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
