<HEADLINE> Egypt Sends Back Suspected Imported Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has returned 10 shipments of
food-stuff that fail to measure up to the health standard to their
exporting countries, Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The shipments, imported from Ireland, the Netherlands, Belgium,
Australia, Cyprus, Greece, Germany, Thailand and Spain, were found
unfit for human consumption and not in compliance with health
specifications, said the English daily.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Trade and Supply Minister Ahmed Goweily told Al Akhbar
recently that Egypt has sent back 142 tonnes of British beef
imported from the Netherlands that authorities suspected was
tainted with bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) or mad cow
disease.
</P>
<P>
Egypt banned imports of British beef immediately after the
European Union imposed an embargo on the meat in March 1996
because of mad cow disease, which was rampant in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Cairo banned imports of Belgian beef on July 3 after an EU
announcement of a Belgian company's possible involvement in
exporting British beef.
</P>
<P>
It returned 25,000 tonnes of Belgian beef considered unfit for
consumption and burned 519 tonnes of French beef for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, crackdowns on food production factories last month
in Alexandria, the country's second largest city, resulted in
destroying about 7,657 tonnes of foodstuffs which were found to be
unfit for human consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
