<HEADLINE> Bailong River Area to Become Major Oil Olive Base For China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bailong River Valley in
northwest China's Gansu Province will plant about 2,700 ha of
olives by the year 2000, making the area an important oil olive
base.
</P>
<P>
Oil olive, which was originally produced around the
Mediterranean Sea, was introduced to China in 1964, and since
then, the Bailong river area, with its unique weather patterns,
has been discovered to be the best place for growing olives in
China.
</P>
<P>
The fruit of the olive tree contains a number of vitamins and
other substances that are good for health.
</P>
<P>
The local government has been treating oil olive as a pillar
industry for development. In 1996, the State spent 17 million yuan
on the effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
