<HEADLINE> Northwest China Planting More Special Pear Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The acreage for growing Korla sweet
pears, a special product of China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, will increase to 8,000 ha in three years, with annual
output expected to reach 80,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Korla City planted 6,700 ha of the trees by the end of last
year, making it the largest pear base in China. Output was 22,000
tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The pears are now exported, via Hong Kong, to Singapore,
Canada, and elsewhere and sales on the domestic market are on the
rise, local officials say.
</P>
<P>
The sugar content of the pear can reach as high as ten percent,
and the Vitamin C content, 4.5 percent, and 84 percent of the pear
can be eaten.  
</P>
