<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Upgrade Road System in Mekong River Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has drawn
a plan to build a road in the Mekong River Delta, linking Ho Chi
Minh City with other southern economic centers, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The total investment for the project is estimated at 3,500
billion Vietnamese dong (about 300 million U.S. dollars) by the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The government has invested over 1,000 billion dong (about 85
million dollars) in upgrading and rehabilitating the road system
in the Mekong River Delta in a bid to boost regional social and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The upgrade of the National Highway 1, which serves as the sole
route linking the delta provinces with Ho Chi Minh City, is
expected to be complete by 2000 together with the completion of
two bridges crossing the tributaries of the Mekong River.
</P>
<P>
Apart from funds from the government, provincial authorities
will also collect money from local people to construct roads
connecting national highways with townships and district towns to
better serve economic development.
</P>
<P>
The 36,000-square-kilometer Mekong River Delta is the biggest
agricultural region in Vietnam, accounting for 40 percent of the
country's total agricultural output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
