<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Tourists in Egypt on Spending Spree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Arab tourists have come to
Egypt in droves this years, each spending, in just on month, more
than three times the average Egyptian earns in a year, Middle East
Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The number of Arab tourists to Egypt has risen 14.5 percent to
361,324 during January-July this year, the English weekly said in
its latest edition, quoting tourism officials.
</P>
<P>
Citizens from the United Arab Emirates, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Bahrain, Qatar and Iraq are making Egypt their summer vacation
spot, according to Nazmy Amin, undersecretary of state for the
Egyptian Tourist Authority (ETA).
</P>
<P>
According to an ETA report, the average amount a Gulf Arab
spends per day while in Egypt is 136 U.S. dollars, or 4,080 per
month, while World Bank figures show the average annual Egyptian
salary is 1,200 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Much of the reason for the rise in Arab tourism comes from a
one million U.S. dollar marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Tourism, along with the Egyptian Hotel
Association and other government agencies, have targeted the Gulf
region and boosted the amount of advertising on Egypt, especially
the Red Sea coast.
</P>
<P>
The increase in entertainment such as bowling centers, golf
courses and restaurants had also added new life and fun, according
to Tourism Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Arabs visiting Egypt would frequent Cairo and
Alexandria and spend their time for leisure and entertainment in
shopping malls, night clubs and theaters.
</P>
<P>
But this year, the trend has shifted to an interest in
Hurghada, Luxor and Sharm Al Sheikh, spots famous for their
archeological and scenic attractions.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf tourists come to Egypt instead of going to European
summer destinations, say most, because they feel strong ties with
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Another major pull has been investment opportunities. Joint
ventures and commercial tourism possibilities are tempting for Gulf
Arabs who have already began to build houses, tourism villages and
commercial centers in Cairo and the Sinai.
</P>
<P>
The best year for tourism was 1992 as a result of a big
publicity campaign and the worst was just one year later due to
terrorism and an earthquake, according to ETA.
</P>
<P>
The largest group of Arab tourists come from Saudi Arabia,
numbering 68,659, up 7.8 percent, followed by Kuwait, United Arab
Emirates, Qatar and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Invites ILO Expert to Help Revise Labor Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has invited an expert
from the Interantional Labor Organization to help revise the
country's new draft labor law which provides for many changes to
benefit laborers - Kuwaitis and expatriates.
</P>
<P>
According to Khalil Al-Onaizi, assistant undersecretary for
legal affairs of the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, said
here today the ILO expert will arrive within the coming few days.
</P>
<P>
Al-Onaizi said the expert would prepare a report on the bill
and the report would be taken into consideration.
</P>
<P>
The draft labor law, finalized by the Ministry of Social
Affairs and Labor last month, grants laborers more end-of-service
indemnity, increases annual public holidays and sick leave and
introduces more safety measures and certain other new benefits for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
The law, after approval, would cover all employees, Kuwaiti
and expatriates, working in the private and oil sectors, in which
about 80 percent of the employees are foreigners, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Onaizi said the new draft law has not dealt with the issue
of Kuwaiti sponsorship required for expatriate laborers, but it
allows the setting up of special recruitment agencies to provide
the needed employees to businessmen from inside and outside the
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to eradicate the rampant visa smuggling, the draft
law bans employers from hiring expatriates without the necessary
permission from the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor.
</P>
<P>
It also forbids businessmen from recruiting laborers from
outside Kuwait and fail to provide them with jobs, stipulating a
jail term up to three years and a fine of 16,500 U.S. dollars for
violators.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently has more than 600,000 foreign laborers and
the government has been striving to increase the percentage of
local employees in the private sector as well as in the
state-owned economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
The draft law will be submitted to the Cabinet and then to
Kuwaiti National Assembly for approval. Officials expect the it be
approved and come into effect before the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
