<HEADLINE> Khatami Appoints Habibi as First Vice-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's new President Mohammad
Khatami, few hours after being sworn in, appointed Hassan Habibi,
the second man in the administration of former President Hashemi
Rafsanjani, as his first vice-president.
</P>
<P>
In his decree, Khatami said that Habibi was appointed on the
basis of his "scientific and educational background, religious and
moral qualifications and experience in the administrative affairs
of the country."
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the official news agency IRNA, the
appointment is made according to the article 124 of Iran's
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
This was the first appointment made by the new president, who
said early today that he will introduce his cabinet to the
Parliament soon.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Habibi is seen here as the new president's
determination to keep Rafsanjani's economic policy and the
post-war reconstruction program, especially the Second Five-Year
Development Plan from 1996 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
Habibi served as first vice-president under the administration
of Rafsanjani, who ran the country in the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
Habibi, 61, the son of Mirza Baqer Habibi, a shop-owner at
Tehran's bazaar, is well respected in the academic circle. He is
known as an academician, with no blemish on his integrity.
</P>
<P>
Raised in a strictly religious environment, Habibi got involved
in the religious circles that were rallying to overthrow the late
Shah in 1960s.
</P>
<P>
He fled to France in early 1960s after he was sought for his
political activities by the Shah's secret police. There he pursued
his academic career in sociology and received his doctorate. He
was also one of the leaders of the anti-Shah student movement in
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
