<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
weaker in Sydney today after a quiet local session which was
dulled by the absence of many market participants because of a
bank holiday in the state of New South Wales and Canberra.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the Australian dollar had traded in a narrow
range, after being pushed below 74 US cents by a round of selling
during offshore overnight dealings in New York and London on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
It closed lower at 73.94 US cents, from 74.45 US cents
previously.
</P>
<P>
Bankers Trust Australia senior dealer Geoff Bowmer said the
market had further tested the downsize today to see the unit tap
an intraday low of 73.65 US cents.
</P>
<P>
But buying interest from exporters soon saw the Australian
dollar recover back towards 73.80 to 73.90 US cents.
</P>
<P>
In the near term, the local unit was seen capped on the top at
74.10 US cents, while the downsize looked limited to 73.60 to
73.70 US cents.
</P>
<P>
Over the week, the Australian dollar was seen trading between
73.10 and 74.50 US cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 87.55 yen, from 88.56, and at
1.3783 marks, from 1.3756 previously.  
</P>
