<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenhouse Gas Emissions on Rise in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Greenhouse gas emissions are
rising in Britain, making the country's combat against global
warming more difficult, Cambridge Econometrics said in a report
released today.
</P>
<P>
"Carbon emissions are projected to rise over the next
five to 10 years largely due to growing road transport and
power generation demand," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that by the year 2010 Britain's emissions are expected
to be less than four percent below 1990 levels. Under current
government policy emissions would only start to fall by 2008.
</P>
<P>
The British government has promised to cut its emissions of
carbon dioxide, the main greenhouse gas, by 20 percent from 1990
levels by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The report said indications from the government that it might
encourage coal power stations could further hamper reductions.
</P>
</TEXT>
