<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Finishes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market lost
ground today, taking the lead from New York's negative finish on
Friday, while the bank holiday in Sydney and other part of the New
South Wales state contributed to a drab day of trading.
</P>
<P>
"The bank holiday didn't help much, leaving the market to drift
with the negative influence from Wall Street," Henderson Charlton
Jones broker Philip Toop said.
</P>
<P>
"The resource stocks fared better than the industrials and the
banks due to some reasonable commodity prices on Friday night."
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index shed 21.5 points to close at 2706.0,
after the Dow Jones industrial average fell 28.57 points on Friday
to finish at 8194.04.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index dropped 36.6 points to 4349.5, while
the resources index slipped 9.6 to 1425.1.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is a general feeling in the market now that the
resources will experience stronger earnings growth over the next
18 months than the industrials sector," Toop said.
</P>
<P>
"So there's a more positive underlying tone for the resources."
</P>
<P>
Among today's leaders, mining giant BHP lost 16 cents to finish
at 17.85 Australian dollars and mining company Rio Tinto fell 12.3
to 20.67 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, ANZ was hardest hit, losing 19 cents to
10.51 Australian dollars, followed by Westpac, which finished 16
weaker at 8.46 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank shed 14 to 19.37 Australian
dollars, CBA was 12 softer at 16.53 Australian dollars and St
George Bank also dipped 14 cents to 8.81 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached just 223.94 million shares, worth
448.04 million Australian dollars (331.54 million US dollars).
Falls outpaced rises, 601 to 332, with 414 steady.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion was trading 1.00 US dollar weaker at 323.70 US
dollars while the gold index lost 13.9 points at 1324.0.  
</P>
</TEXT>
