<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Levy Meet on Containing Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
will meet with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy Wednesday in a
bid to contain the volatile situation in the Mideast and salvage
the teetering peace march.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said today that he had
invited Levy to Egypt for talks on ending the deteriorating peace
crisis following last week's suicide bombings in a Jerusalem
market which killed 15 people and injured 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that Levy is expected to arrive in Egypt
later today.
</P>
<P>
Asked about whether the current Egyptian-Palestinian-U.S.
contacts could serve as a new starting point for the peace
process, Moussa said that "all depends on what the parties
(Palestinians and Israelis) can offer within the framework of the
implementation of the Oslo agreement."
</P>
<P>
"The two parties are requested to implement the agreement while
observing calmness, composure and self-restraint," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross is expected in the region
late this week for talks with Arab and Israeli officials on a new
U.S. initiative. Ross' scheduled trip here last week was put off
after the double suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Ambassador to Israel Mohammed Bassyouni told Voice of
Arab radio today that current Egyptian efforts are exerted to have
the transitional stage implemented and obstacles to the peace
march removed.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Israeli contact will coincide with an Arab League
council meeting to be held here tomorrow at the request of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to study the crucial
situation facing the Palestinians as a result of Israel's tough
measures and closure in the wake of the bombing attack.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leadership called those measures and
culminating Israeli threat to re-enter areas of Palestinian
self-rule as "a declaration of war" against the PNA and the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Since last Wednesday, Israel has imposed a closure on the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, barring tens of thousands of Palestinians
from jobs in Israel and restricting even Palestinians' movements
between their autonomous West Bank towns.
</P>
<P>
It also closed the Palestinian international crossing-points
with Egypt and Jordan and suspended the transfer of tax and
customs revenues to the PNA coffer.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been trying to revive Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
which stalled after Israel broke ground on a Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
