<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Terracotta Warriors Unearthed In Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The mausoleum of China's first
emperor in Shaanxi province has yielded even more terracotta
warriors in various positions: kneeling down to shoot, leading a
horse, or standing in a chariot drawn by four horses.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that these figures from Pit No. Two
are different from their companions that were brought to light
earlier, which are mainly foot soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The terracotta warriors, serving as a netherworld guard for Qin
Shi Huang, the first unifier of China and founder for the Qin
Dynasty (221-206 BC), were buried in three pits in the
mausoleum. They were discovered in 1974 when a local farmer was
digging a well.
</P>
<P>
Pits No. One and Three were excavated and opened to public by
1979 and 1989, respectively, and soon became known world-wide as
the "Eighth Wonder of the World."
</P>
<P>
Pit No. Two was regarded as the cream of the crop, but was not
excavated until March 1994 and was opened to the public later that
year, while the excavation was still under way. Archaeologists
have now removed all the earth over them, exposing a layer of
beams above the terracotta figures.
</P>
<P>
There are 1,350 beams covering a 3,000-sq. m. area, about half
of the pit, which are in good shape except for a few decayed or
burned that have collapsed, and 86 terracotta warriors and 44
horses and carriages have been excavated. The scientists say they
are unique.
</P>
<P>
In the process of clearing 11 doorways to the pit, the
archaeologists found traces of digging by iron tools, ditches
where water ran while the pit was being dug, wheeltracks,
footprints of the pit diggers, and traces of earthworms.
</P>
<P>
To the scientists' surprise, two tombs from the Eastern Han
Dynasty (25-220) were found above the terracotta figures,
suggesting that people may have discovered the pits some 1,800
years ago.
</P>
<P>
What is even more amazing is a hole perhaps dug by tomb robbers
from the Han dynasty (206 BC-220 AD) leading to the rare
terracotta carriage drawn by four horses. Fortunately the carriage
was not the target of the treasure seekers.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists are now planning to excavate the
beam layer, while leaving a few beams for display. They will
repair some of the terracotta figures and leaving others in
fragments.
</P>
<P>
"That will impress visitors by showing them how the relics
looked before being repaired," the scientists explain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
