<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese Province's Economic Promotion Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a traditional
industrial base in northeast China, is working to remove three
major roadblocks to economic development.
</P>
<P>
The problems include poorly-operating state enterprises, lack
of efficiency in use of capital, and the state's grain buying,
selling, and storage system.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning plans to take three years to make medium-sized and
large state firms responsible for their own profits and losses and
to let them compete in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
The province is going to try to improve its grain market. The
local state system of buying and selling has run in the red for
too long, and steps are to be taken to remove present barriers and
provide a long-term grain market goal.
</P>
<P>
Governor Wen Shizhen told Xinhua that the three schemes are
important for the province's overall economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
