<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 08:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Spy In U.S. Angered By Minister's Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Johnathan Pollard, serving a
life sentence for spying on the U.S. for Israel, has refused to
meet with an Israeli Embassy official because of a statement by
Israeli Justice Minister.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Justice minister Tzahi Hanegbi had made a
suggestion that Pollard be transferred to an Israeli jail,
reported the pro-government newspaper, The Jerusalem Post, today.
</P>
<P>
"While the government of Israel is busy stabbing me in the
back," Pollard, an American Jew, said in a letter to the Israeli
Ambassador Eliahu Ben-Elissar to Washington, he would not meet
with the Israeli official.
</P>
<P>
The visit, which the embassy initiated and scheduled to
coincide with Pollard's 43rd birthday Thursday, would have been
the first-ever by an embassy official. Pollard was granted
Israeli citizenship by the previous Labor government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Pollard wrote that Hanegbi's remarks, suggesting he serve the
remainder of his sentence in an Israeli jail, were "fraudulent
 ... calculated and without honor."
</P>
<P>
Hanegbi, who was referring to a new law which makes possible
prisoner transfers, said here Sunday night that "Israel will
respect Pollard's wishes and in any event will only act on the
subject (the prisoner transfer) if he puts in a request. "Pollard
first has to complete a formal request before Israel would take
any action," he Hanegbi added.
</P>
<P>
Pollard asked in his letter that how could Hanegbi
"returning a prisoner of Zion to Zion in chains? It was this
same cold-blooded cynicism that was evidenced when the government
of Israel threw me, an Israeli agent, out of the embassy" 13
years ago. He added that the current government has "escalated
... the degree of cold-blooded calculation and cynicism."
</P>
<P>
Pollard's wife, Esther Zeitz-Pollard, said in a statement that
it would take years before a prisoner-exchange accord between the
U.S. and Israel was formalized, and Israel would not be able to
legally parole Pollard without American consent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year Pollard's relatives accused Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu of lacking enthusiasm in personally appealing
to President Bill Clinton to free Pollard when he visited
Washington, as his predecessors, Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres,
did. 
</P>
</TEXT>
