<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 07:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search for Missing Israeli Submarine Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Navy's nuclear
submarine NR-1 will continue the search for a missing Israeli
submarine off the coast of Egypt, reported the pro-government
newspaper, The Jerusalem Post, today.
</P>
<P>
The search will be conducted outside Egyptian territorial
waters with the cooperation of Egyptian authorities, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ship has been searching for the Dakar, the Israeli
Navy's submarine that sank in January 1968, in the Aegean Sea for
the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Israeli Navy chief of personnel, a former
submarine force commander whose name was not disclosed in
accordance with Israeli laws, at a press conference aboard the
NR-1's tender in Haifa Bay Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Dakar, originally the HMS Totem, was built in 1944 and
purchased from Britain in June 1965 as part of a two-sub deal. It
sailed from Portmouth on January 9, 1968, en route to Haifa, where
it was to formally join the Israeli Navy, with a crew of 69.
</P>
<P>
On January 24, the Dakar, which was then south of Mediterranean
island of Crete, radioed navy headquarters for the last time,
saying it had made better time than planned and seeking permission
to arrive early. The request was denied, because the Navy did not
want the submarine arriving before the scheduled ceremony, which
the prime minister was to attend.
</P>
<P>
On February 4, the submarine was declared sunk and its crew
missing. On February 9, 1969, the Dakar's emergency buoy was found
by an Arab fisherman off the coast of Khan Yunis, Gaza Strip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
