<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Record Growth In Foreign Trade, GDP, Foreign Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China's growth in imports and
exports in the past five years has made it one of the world's
foreign trade powers, the State Statistics Bureau reports.
</P>
<P>
Today's Guangming Daily quotes bureau statistics showing China
with 289.9 billion US dollars worth of imports and exports in
1996, a figure that is 1.7 times bigger than that for 1992, when
the Chinese Communist Party's 14th National Congress was held.
</P>
<P>
Its foreign currency reserves have increased a great deal
during the same period, up from 19.44 billion US dollars in 1992
to 105 billion US dollars by the end of last year, putting them
among the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
China's Gross Domestic Product more than doubled from 1992 to
last year, going from 2.66 trillion yuan to 6.77 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that in 1992 the country had a daily GDP
of over five billion yuan, and it jumped to 18.57 billion yuan in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
