<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Economic Growing In Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The private economy in China's
Qinghai Province developed rapidly in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, there were 67,000 household businesses in
the province, employing 100,000 people, with 492 million yuan in
capital.
</P>
<P>
The number of larger-scale private businesses in the province
rose to 2,100, with 26,000 employees, and 1.2 billion in
registered capital.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai is a remote inland province in the northwestern part of
China. Because of a lack of information, the province has lagged
behind other provinces in developing the private economy. By the
end of 1990, there were only 4,500 household businesses and 362
larger-scale private firms in the province.
</P>
<P>
But, the sector has seen faster growth since 1995, when
industrial and commercial departments at various levels began to
help by offering information and solving entrepreneurs' problems.
</P>
<P>
Taxes paid by these two types of business amounted to 126
million yuan in 1996, accounting for seven percent of the
province's total revenues.
</P>
<P>
And they provided jobs for 10,000 laid-off workers in the first
half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
