<HEADLINE> Lebanon Seeks Unified Arab Front against Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Defense Minister Mohsen
Dalloul Sunday lashed at the U.S. for failing to be an unbiased
sponsor of the peace process, calling for unified Arab front to
defend their interests against Israeli threats.
</P>
<P>
"The best way to retaliate Israel's stubbornness and
U.S. partiality is to set up a joint Arab front in which all
member countries are aware that their interests are threatened,"
Dalloul said, quoted by the Daily Star newspaper here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing popular delegations at Manara in the western Beqaa,
Dalloul called on the U.S. "to play the role of a neutral and
honest mediator in the Arab-Israeli conflict," adding that
"visits by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and peace
coordinator Dennis Ross to the region will be futile as long as
the biased policy of the U.S. has not changed."
</P>
<P>
He criticized Qatar for planning to host an economic
cooperation conference in November with Israel's attendance,
saying Doha's argument that the meeting would boost the peace
process "is ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
He described last week's double suicide bombings in Jerusalem
as "a natural consequence of the stalemated peace talks and the
crimes perpetrated by Zionists in many places."
</P>
<P>
Anti-Israeli attacks "are poised to continue as long as the
talks have not been restarted on the basis of just and
comprehensive peace and the principles agreed at the Madrid
conference," in which the peace process was launched in 1991,
Dalloul said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
