<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Economy Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's economy has begun to
recover from its lowest point, despite the haunting effects of the
case of the financially troubled Kia Group.
</P>
<P>
Consumption in the private sector has been going up since June,
and facility and construction investment has also started to
increase, said the Ministry of Finance and Economy.
</P>
<P>
Citing as signs of the recovery, the ministry said the
country's exports in July grew at the highest rate so far this
year, while production activities continued to boom.
</P>
<P>
Sales of air-conditioners and beverages soared sharply amid
sizzling weather, and high sales of automobiles also contributed
to the revitalization of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The ministry previously predicted that the economy would hit
rock bottom around September or October.
</P>
<P>
The National Statistics Office also came up with data on the
national trend of industrial activities, featuring a 12.4 percent
rise in industrial output in June, compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Given the effect in the wake of strikes at major automobile
plants, the growth rate reached 9.7 percent, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Delivery of consumer products in domestic markets, which
dwindled 0.3 percent in May, rose 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In facility investment, the decrease rate was down from May's
8.0 percent to 0.1 percent, while investment in construction rose
48.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shipments increased a remarkable 19.7 percent in July when
exports grew 27.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry estimated that industrial output, delivery and
shipments would continue to increase in July, strengthening the
foundation for the national economic recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
