<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minimum Wages Fixed in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has fixed
the minimum wages and dearness allowance for the employees of
industry, transport, tourism and other departments except the tea
estates, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government stipulated that unskilled employees should get a
minimum monthly salary of 1,300 rupees (about 23 U.S. dollars),
semi-skilled should get 1,350 rupees (24 dollars), skilled 1,460
rupees (26 dollars), highly-skilled 1,650 rupees (29 dollars) and
employees in the 14-16 age group 1,025 rupees (18 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Likewise, all the employees will get a dearness allowance of
500 rupees (8.8 dollars), up 50 rupees (90 U.S. cents) over what
they get now.
Employees in the 14-16 age group will get 375 rupees (6.6 dollars)
every month, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Those working on a daily wage basis will be given 63 rupees
(1.1 dollars) a day, while workers in the 14-16 age group will be
given 50 rupees (90 cents) a day.
</P>
<P>
The working hour for workers in this age group has been fixed
at six hours a day, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The government stressed that men and women should be given
equal wage and allowance for similar work.
</P>
<P>
The minimum wage rule came as recommended by a tripartite
committee comprising the Ministry of Labor, the Federation of
Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry and the trade unions.
</P>
<P>
And the government's new budget for the fiscal year 1997-98
also decided to increase the wages of employees and workers.
</P>
<P>
Prices of some commodities, including oil products, have gone
up in Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
