<HEADLINE> 4,000 Tamil Civilians Stranded in Eastern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Over 4,000 Tamil civilians are
stranded in Trincomalee town in the East of Sri Lanka, awaiting to
be ferried to Jaffna Peninsula in the North, according to reports
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
While four ships are available for the purpose, the owners of
the vessels are unwilling to expose the safety of their vessels
and crew to possible attacks by rebels of the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam (LTTE) who have been fighting for a separate state in
the north and east of the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE attacked several vessels carrying commodities to the
North from Colombo last month.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross has failed to
negotiate with the LTTE to escort the civilian ferries, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, those who had left their home due to
the fighting and were awaiting transport to the North, were mainly
teachers, students, workers, elderly persons and children.
</P>
