<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Stresses Ocean Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zhehai Oceanic Survey ship
departed Weihai Wharf late last month, marking the end of a
month-long comprehensive coastal waters environmental survey in
the Bohai and Huanghai Districts.
</P>
<P>
This survey, sponsored by China's National Environmental
Protection Agency, yielded valuable data concerning offshore
water quality and sources of pollution.
</P>
<P>
Besides the survey, the Chinese government has enacted a number
of related laws and regulations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Rapid local economic development focusing on the offshore oil
industry, ocean shipping and saltwater aquiculture has greatly
increased the volume of effluent industrial wastewater and
domestic flowing into the sea. Effluent discharges have led to
increasingly serious levels of offshore pollution.
</P>
<P>
Departments under the Offshore Environment Supervision Network
and Zhejiang Provincial Oceanic Ecological Environment Supervision
Station provided full support for the survey in order to
accelerate regional economic development.
</P>
<P>
The 257 supervision stations established in the districts are
responsible for monitoring 148 areas related to hydrology,
meteorology, sources of both land and sea pollution, aquiculture,
seabed deposits, offshore water quality, and effluent
discharges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
