<HEADLINE> US Senate Classifies Sri Lankan Rebels as Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The United States Senate has
unanimously recommended that the Clinton administration should
list Sri Lanka's Liberation Tigers of Tamil Ealam as a terrorist
organization, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has also urged that the Clinton administration
should expand its support for the anti-terrorist program in Sri
Lanka, the newspaper quoted Foreign Ministry sources here as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation was passed last week as an amendment during
the Senate debate on the Appropriation Act of 1998 for the conduct
of foreign operations and related programs.
</P>
<P>
This is in the context of the Anti-Terrorist and Effective
Death Penalty Act of 1996 which authorizes the U.S. Secretary of
State to designate an organization as a foreign terrorist
organization.
</P>
<P>
So far the U.S. State Department has not listed any foreign
terrorist organization as authorized by this legislation.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the U.S. Senate stated reportedly that it was
concerned about the alarming toll that Tamil terrorists have taken
on innocent civilians in Sri Lanka, and urged the administration
to seriously consider making 750,000 U.S. dollars available in
anti-terrorism funds to combat this problem. 
</P>
