<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Spur Shenzhen Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's return to the
motherland on July 1 has acted as a spur to healthy and stable
economic growth in south China's Shenzhen City, a special economic
zone bordering Hong Kong, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen generated more than 46 billion yuan in GDP during the
first half of this year, up 16.5 percent over the same period in
1996. Industrial production rose by 20 percent to 60.3 billion
yuan during the six-month period and fixed asset investment went
up by 22.3 percent to 14.72 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Sales volume hit nearly 15 billion yuan during the period, up
8.5 percent from the same period in 1996, with production-to-sale
ratio reaching 97.4 percent. And the price index has been
controlled at below 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city conducted more than 20 billion yuan in foreign trade
during the six-month period, up 14.3 percent on a year-on-year
basis. It actually used more than 1.3 billion US dollars of
overseas investment, up 50 percent over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the balance of bank deposits has reached
163.62 billion yuan, up 6.9 percent compared with the beginning of
the year. Securities trade volume hit 1,214.25 billion yuan in the
first two quarters of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
