<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China More Experienced in Balancing Good Harvest and Crop Failures (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China has seen two major
ups-and-downs in grain production that have forced it to confront
the market fluctuations in the past 13 years, and now has enough
experience to balance successful harvests and crop failures,
Chinese economists say.
</P>
<P>
In the lean years of 1985-86 and 1991-92, there was famine in
some areas and grain prices shot up, bringing a handsome profit to
speculators and causing farmers and urban dwellers to suffer.
</P>
<P>
The state put large quantities of grain on the market through
state-owned grain stores and imported grain to satisfy domestic
needs.
</P>
<P>
Good harvests are both happy and worrisome events. They often
lead to overstocking, an insufficient number of warehouses, a
reluctance by grain importers to purchase grain, and a drop in
price, putting a damper on farmers' enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
To protect grain growers' interests and to stabilize the
market, in 1990 the Chinese Government started to set up a minimum
grain price system and the special grain reserve system. In 1994,
a grain market risk fund system was set up at provincial levels
and above.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the Central Government began asking grain
producers in the Northeast and in Inner Mongolia to ship a certain
amount of grain to the South for storage.
</P>
<P>
These have had a positive effect, giving China a greater
ability to hold grain market risks down, according to Xie Yang, a
research fellow at the State Council's Development and Research
Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China More Experienced in Balancing Good Harvest and Crop Failures (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This year's summer grain output has been estimated at 123
billion kg, 10 billion more than in the peak year of 1996.
</P>
<P>
This has affected summer grain purchases. Farmers in some areas
still have a great amount of grain on their hands after filling
state quotas and see the price take a nosedive when they try to
sell it on the market.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body, decided
earlier this month to buy surplus grain without limit at a
protected price of 1.38 yuan per kg, and assured grain growers
they would make a profit.
</P>
<P>
This decision was praised by farmers all over the country, and
grain growers queued up outside state-run grain collection centers
each day.
</P>
<P>
One farmer, Liu Qiying, not long ago planned to reduce the
grain growing acreage in his hometown in Henan Province, a leading
grain producer, but told Xinhua that he would grow more grain next
year.
</P>
<P>
Summer grain output in Henan accounted for a third of the
nation's total. The Central Government policy had the enthusiastic
support of 80 million farmers in Henan, and the state has urged
townships to build more temporary warehouses and make full use of
unused ones. State banks have allocated 1.5 billion yuan for grain
storage expansion loans.
</P>
<P>
The government has also encouraged farmers to hold on to grain
and has promised to buy it later.
</P>
<P>
Li Yingzhong, a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of
Agricultural Sciences says that a major task after a good harvest
is to keep farmers' enthusiasm for growing grain high to avoid a
possible drop in production.
</P>
<P>
Han Xiling, a professor at the Ministry of Internal Trade's
Zhengzhou Grain Institute, called the protected price a new way
for the socialist market economy to regulate the grain market. And
a State Planning Commission official says the move is an effective
method of increasing reforms in the grain system and improving the
grain market system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China's Rich Ore Deposits Give Promise of High Yields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A number of newly discovered
mineral deposits in southwestern China indicate a bright future
for another non-ferrous metal production base for the country,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a large copper deposit explored in Simao in
Yunnan Province, gold deposits with promising reserves were
discovered in Lijiang, Zhongdian and Heqing counties of the
province during the first half of this year, according to the
Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources.
</P>
<P>
During the last few years, over 10 large mines have been
discovered in the counties crossed by "three rivers," namely the
Nujiang, the Lancang and the Jinsha Rivers. With a total area of
160,000 square kilometers, the "three rivers" region is believed
to be unusually rich in precious and non-ferrous metals.
</P>
<P>
The proven reserves of copper alone in the region will possibly
top 10 million tons, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is confident in the finding of 5,000 tons of
silver reserves and 50 tons of gold reserves in the region by the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The State Planning Commission and the ministry has jointly
drafted a plan to intensify the prospecting of mineral resources
in the region. The two organizations will spend five to eight
years to work out a comprehensive report about mineral resources
distribution in the region.
</P>
<P>
General survey of mineral resources in the area will be intensified
and investment in the similar surveys and paid use of the rights
for prospecting will be encouraged, according to the
ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Unemployment Rate Major Task In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Bringing China's high rate of
unemployment down is a primary goal of the macro-economic
controls, according to monthly magazine "Outlook".
</P>
<P>
It says that the real rate of unemployment in urban areas was
7.5 percent by the end of the first quarter of this year, at 15.5
million people. This was 4.5 percent higher than 1996's three
percent, or 5.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
Rural areas have 175 million surplus labourers, representing an
unemployment rate of 34.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The higher unemployment rate is attributed to a contradiction
between a large amount of labor but few funds, large scale
industrial readjustment, an increasing number of lay-offs at
state-owned enterprises, and the high rate of economic growth and
investment.
</P>
<P>
Labor is China's richest resource, but how to make use of it is
a key link to sustained economic growth. China needs to develop
labor-intensive industries and a policy of saving capital while
using more workers.
</P>
<P>
There are a number of ways to reduce unemployment, according to
the magazine:
</P>
<P>
-- Enlarge the service industry in food service, commerce, and
tourism;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop the non-state economy and help it to absorb laid-off
workers;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop small labor-intensive enterprises by providing them
with loans;
</P>
<P>
-- Encourage unemployed urban dwellers to open small businesses;
</P>
<P>
-- Support foreign trade based on labor-intensive industries,
and
</P>
<P>
-- Develop more labor markets and job agencies, especially for
those who have no special skills, and set up unemployment and
old-age insurance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
