<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Thredbo disaster survivor Stuart Diver thanked his rescuers
for his life and the nation for its prayers Sunday as more than
600 workers risked further landslides to search for ten of his
friends buried beneath tons of wreckage.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- A flood of teenagers went back to school because they can no
longer get the dole, the federal government was forced to consider
up to 140 million Australian dollars (105 million U.S. dollars) in
new measures to help the education system.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Former Queensland premier Wayne Goss would struggle to
defeat independent MP Pauline Hanson in the seat of Oxley,
Opposition leader Kim Beazley said Sunday, warning that if Hanson
beat Goss it would send an appalling signal to the Asia-Pacific
region.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The most concerted and costly recruitment drive by the
Australian Council of Trade Unions has failed with the nation's 20
biggest unions suffering a loss of more than 86,000 members in the
past two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
