<DOCNO> XIE19970804.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greene and Jones Caps World Fastest Man and Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- powerful rising stars Maurice Greene
and Marion Jones blazed down the track sizzling fast to win the men's
and women's 100-meter titles for the United States with the season's
best times at the current 6th World Athletics Championships here
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Greene upset world record holder and Olympic champion Donovan
Bailey of Canada in the final with a clocking of 9.86 seconds, the
fourth best time in history and only 0.02 seconds shy of the world
record.
</P>
<P>
"The Lord was helping me to have the grace today. I said that I
would bring the American sprint back and this was the start of this
aim," said a beamed Greene after his triumph.
</P>
<P>
"My acceleration was very good. In a 100m race you can only win and
the world record will come," he added.
</P>
<P>
Bailey, who beat Michael Johnson in the million-dollar 150 meters
race on June 1, equalled his year's best mark in 9.91 to nail the
silver. The bronze medal was won by another American Tim Montgomery,
who taped 9.94.
</P>
<P>
"Until 60 meters I was racing well. Then another Bailey was
running. Greene won and that's about it. I'm looking for excuses, I
have just had too many problems this season," said Bailey, who has
been plagued by leg injuries this year.
</P>
<P>
The pre-race favourite Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tobago
disappointed the crowd with a fifth finish in 10.02, much slower than
his second round clocking of 9.87 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Olympic silver winner Frank Fredericks of Namibia cruised home
fourth in 9.95.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 100m showdown, Jones lived up to the prediction when
she hit the tape with a 10.83 seconds, the year's fastest time and
0.06 seconds inside her personal best.
</P>
<P>
Two less-known sprinters raked up the silver and bronze. Zhanna
Pintussevich of Ukraine wound up second in 10.85 and Sevatheda Fynes
of Bahams third in 11.03.
</P>
<P>
The day saw bad luck hit Jamaica's Merlene Ottey again and rob the
37-year-old the last chance to win the 100m world title.
</P>
<P>
Sevatheda jumped at the gun and made a false start, but Ottey
didn't hear the gun. With a determination to compete for the gold, the
Jamaican ran as fast as she could till 70 meters. That coused her too
much power and strength and made her fate doomed.
</P>
<P>
Jones said about the false start:"I have learned that anything that
happens in a race you just have to shake it off. The first gun went
off and Merlene didn't hear it. I was just determined to make my seond
start a little better."
</P>
<P>
The basketballer-turned sprinter added:"This championship is the
tops of my list far and a lot higher than my past basketball career.
The basketball NCAA final was a great experience a couple of years ago
but this is tops. I am definately here to stay for many years."
</P>
<P>
Ottey was out of reaching after the race. No one knows why mishaps
always hit her. The sprinting star was twice nipped at the line by
Gail Devers of the United States at the previous meet and last year's
Olympics. After struggling on the track over 20 years, her dream of
winning the 100m world title has ended like a nightmare tonight.
</P>
<P>
Heinz Weis of Germany claimed the men's hammer gold with a 81.78
toss, beating Andrey Skvaruk of Ukraine and Vasilly Sidorenko of
Russia into second and third places.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's qualifying competitions, defending champion and Olympic
winner Derrick Adkins of the United States was surprisingly eliminated
in the men's 400m hurdles semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Michael Johnson almost toppled out of the men's 400m semifinals
when the world and Olympic champion eased up in the late stage, but
was pipped by Ibrahima Wade of Senegal. Johnson clocked 45.39 seconds
to finish fourth in the group, placing overall 15th among the 16
qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
The other big names all sailed into next rounds without trouble.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
