<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo's Warring Factions Make Concessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 3 (xinhua) -- Congolese President Pascal
Lissouba and his rival former President Sassou Nguesso have made
concessions in separate negotiations aimed at reviving peace
talks, according to sources monitored here today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Bernard Kolelas, Chairman of the
National Mediation Committee after a meeting with U.N. Special
Envoy Mohammed Sahnoun.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Lissouba has accepted in principle the proposal
to form a transitional government of national unity, and that
Nguesso might moderate his demands.
</P>
<P>
According to Kolelas, Sassou no longer rejects Lissouba's
staying on under the terms of his mandate which expired on August
31.
</P>
<P>
A peace accord will pave the way for international peace
keeping force to be deployed in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks in Libreville, Gabon collapsed last week because
the warring factions could not agree on a transition to
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
